{"title_page": "Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety\n| nativename      =\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      =\n| abbreviation    = KDPS\n| fictional       =\n| patch           =\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            =\n| logocaption     =\n| badge           =\n| badgecaption    =\n| flag            =\n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           =\n| mottotranslated =\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = 1983\n| formedmonthday  =\n| preceding1      =\n| dissolved       =\n| superseding     = Kalamazoo Police Department and Kalamazoo Fire Department\n| employees       = 327\n| volunteers      =\n| budget          =\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = United States\n| countryabbr     = USA\n| national        =\n| federal         =\n| international   =\n| divtype         = State\n| divname         = Michigan\n| divdab          =\n| subdivtype      =\n| subdivname      =\n| subdivdab       =\n| map             = Kalamazoo County Michigan Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Kalamazoo Highlighted.svg\n| mapcaption      = Location of Kalamazoo within [[Kalamazoo County, Michigan]]\n| sizearea        = 25.11 sq mi (65.03 sq km)\n| sizepopulation  = 74,262 (2010)\n| legaljuris      = [[Kalamazoo, MI]]\n| governingbody   = \n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   =\n| police          = Yes\n| local           = Yes\n| military        =\n| provost         =\n| gendarmerie     =\n| religious       =\n| speciality      =\n| secret          =\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = 150 E. Crosstown Kalamazoo, MI\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| sworntype       = Public Safety Officer\n| sworn           =\n| unsworntype     = Civilian\n| unsworn         =\n| multinational   =\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Karianne Thomas\n| chief1position  = Chief\n| parentagency    =\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     = Station\n| stations        = 7\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =\n| vehicles1       =\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = [http://www.kalamazoopublicsafety.org/ KDPS Website]\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\n\nThe '''Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety''' is the department charged with [[police]], [[Fire department|fire]] and rescue operations in [[Kalamazoo, Michigan]]. It is one of the largest [[Department of Public Safety|public safety departments]] in the nation, with over 200 sworn officers.\n\n==Public safety model==\nThe Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety was one of the original public safety departments in the world.  The Kalamazoo Police Department and Kalamazoo Fire Department were merged in the 1980s with the goal of saving significant tax payer money while increasing the amount of police and fire protection for its citizens.  The merger of the departments was a difficult process on reaching agreement with unions covering the fire department and police department.  The difficult effort of the merger of the departments along with the successes was even noted by the [[United States House of Representatives]] in the [[Congressional Record]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KnCTDK5jxggC&pg=PA7608&lpg=PA7608&dq=Kalamazoo+Department+of+Public+Safety+%22largest+public+safety%22&source=bl&ots=F3Qf3tAtf-&sig=7cCpoGyGBTxjKKIgrhx7Pr4-jLQ&hl=en&ei=1LISTOvuOZLAM4vtpJkL&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CC4Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=United States of America Congressional Record: Merger Platinum Anniversary, Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref>\n\nAs one of the largest public safety departments Kalamazoo Public Safety is now considered a model public safety department and often consults and trains other cities throughout the world on the public safety model.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/27/municipal-debt-union-fight-firefighters-police_n_853956.html|title=Municipal Debt: Police, Fire Department Merger Attempts Spark Union Fights|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IugY8bPDPJ8|title=Multitasking police in Kalamazoo have been at it for years|date=18 February 2013|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.wsbt.com/2011-02-21/police-officer_28617213|title=Brotherhood of Duties: More communities consider different type of public safety|work=schurz-wsbt-tv|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530094709/http://articles.wsbt.com/2011-02-21/police-officer_28617213|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 1995 a grand jury was convened to investigate missing cash and contraband from Kalamazoo Public Safety's evidence room.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcfp.org/browse-media-law-resources/news/records-investigation-missing-drugs-may-remain-secret|title=Records of investigation into missing drugs may remain secret|work=rcfp.org|accessdate=30 May 2015}}{{better source|date=April 2020}}</ref>  Although much of the evidence and investigation still remains secret and the US Attorney declined to prosecute, the city attorney at the time has publicly acknowledged that the incident happened<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2010/09/a_compassionate_listener_newly.html|title=A compassionate listener:  Newly appointed Kalamazoo City Commissioner Robert Cinabro says he has the skills for the job|work=MLive.com|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the department received the results of a year-long, independent study it commissioned on racial targeting. The study showed black drivers were more than twice as likely to be pulled over by police in Kalamazoo than white drivers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2013/09/kalamazoo_public_safety_office_19.html|title=Kalamazoo Public Safety officers target black drivers in traffic stops, racial profiling study concludes|publisher=MLive.com|accessdate=15 April 2020|date=3 September 2013|last=Hall, Jr|first=Rex|work=Kalamazoo Gazette}}</ref>  Since this time the department has been working hard to confront the racial bias in its department and has received international news coverage for attempting to address the racial issues the department acknowledges it has.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/watch/shows/america-tonight/articles/2015/2/23/kalamazoo-police.html|title=Kalamazoo Police Tackle Racial Profiling|work=Al Jazeera America|publisher=aljazeera.com|accessdate=30 May 2015|date=23 February 2020|last=Amin|first=Sameen}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\nOn April 18, 2011, while responding to a shots fired call in Kalamazoo's Edison neighborhood, PSO Eric Zapata was fatally shot. Officer Zapata was the first officer in Kalamazoo to be killed in the line of duty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2012/04/a_year_after_the_death_of_eric.html|title=Officer Eric Zapata remembered: Fellow Kalamazoo officers recall the night he died (Part 1 of 2)|work=MLive.com|accessdate=28 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EW6mPOSX1Ko Kalamazoo Public Safety Promotional Video]\n\n{{Michigan fire departments}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalamazoo Department Of Public Safety}}\n[[Category:Municipal police departments of Michigan]]\n[[Category:Fire departments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Kalamazoo, Michigan]]\n[[Category:1983 establishments in Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety\n| nativename      =\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      =\n| abbreviation    = KDPS\n| fictional       =\n| patch           =\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            =\n| logocaption     =\n| badge           =\n| badgecaption    =\n| flag            =\n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           =\n| mottotranslated =\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = 1983\n| formedmonthday  =\n| preceding1      =\n| dissolved       =\n| superseding     = Kalamazoo Police Department and Kalamazoo Fire Department\n| employees       = 327\n| volunteers      =\n| budget          =\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = United States\n| countryabbr     = USA\n| national        =\n| federal         =\n| international   =\n| divtype         = State\n| divname         = Michigan\n| divdab          =\n| subdivtype      =\n| subdivname      =\n| subdivdab       =\n| map             = Kalamazoo County Michigan Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Kalamazoo Highlighted.svg\n| mapcaption      = Location of Kalamazoo within [[Kalamazoo County, Michigan]]\n| sizearea        = 25.11 sq mi (65.03 sq km)\n| sizepopulation  = 74,262 (2010)\n| legaljuris      = [[Kalamazoo, MI]]\n| governingbody   = \n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   =\n| police          = Yes\n| local           = Yes\n| military        =\n| provost         =\n| gendarmerie     =\n| religious       =\n| speciality      =\n| secret          =\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = 150 E. Crosstown Kalamazoo, MI\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| sworntype       = Public Safety Officer\n| sworn           =\n| unsworntype     = Civilian\n| unsworn         =\n| multinational   =\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Karianne Thomas\n| chief1position  = Chief\n| parentagency    =\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     = Station\n| stations        = 7\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =\n| vehicles1       =\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = [http://www.kalamazoopublicsafety.org/ KDPS Website]\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\n\nThe '''Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety''' is the department charged with [[police]], [[Fire department|fire]] and rescue operations in [[Kalamazoo, Michigan]]. It is one of the largest [[Department of Public Safety|public safety departments]] in the nation, with over 200 sworn officers.\n\n==Public Safety model==\nThe Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety was one of the original public safety departments in the world.  The Kalamazoo Police Department and Kalamazoo Fire Department were merged in the 1980s with the goal of saving significant tax payer money while increasing the amount of police and fire protection for its citizens.  The merger of the departments was a difficult process on reaching agreement with unions covering the fire department and police department.  The difficult effort of the merger of the departments along with the successes was even noted by the [[United States House of Representatives]] in the [[Congressional Record]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KnCTDK5jxggC&pg=PA7608&lpg=PA7608&dq=Kalamazoo+Department+of+Public+Safety+%22largest+public+safety%22&source=bl&ots=F3Qf3tAtf-&sig=7cCpoGyGBTxjKKIgrhx7Pr4-jLQ&hl=en&ei=1LISTOvuOZLAM4vtpJkL&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CC4Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=United States of America Congressional Record: Merger Platinum Anniversary, Kalamazoo Department of Public Safety \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-06-12}}</ref>\n\nAs one of the largest public safety departments Kalamazoo Public Safety is now considered a model public safety department and often consults and trains other cities throughout the world on the public safety model.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/04/27/municipal-debt-union-fight-firefighters-police_n_853956.html|title=Municipal Debt: Police, Fire Department Merger Attempts Spark Union Fights|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IugY8bPDPJ8|title=Multitasking police in Kalamazoo have been at it for years|date=18 February 2013|work=YouTube|accessdate=28 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.wsbt.com/2011-02-21/police-officer_28617213|title=Brotherhood of Duties: More communities consider different type of public safety|work=schurz-wsbt-tv|accessdate=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530094709/http://articles.wsbt.com/2011-02-21/police-officer_28617213|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 1995 a grand jury was convened to investigate missing cash and contraband from Kalamazoo Public Safety's evidence room.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcfp.org/browse-media-law-resources/news/records-investigation-missing-drugs-may-remain-secret|title=Records of investigation into missing drugs may remain secret|work=rcfp.org|accessdate=30 May 2015}}{{better source|date=April 2020}}</ref>  Although much of the evidence and investigation still remains secret and the US Attorney declined to prosecute, the city attorney at the time has publicly acknowledged that the incident happened<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2010/09/a_compassionate_listener_newly.html|title=A compassionate listener:  Newly appointed Kalamazoo City Commissioner Robert Cinabro says he has the skills for the job|work=MLive.com|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the department received the results of a year-long, independent study it commissioned on racial targeting. The study showed black drivers were more than twice as likely to be pulled over by police in Kalamazoo than white drivers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2013/09/kalamazoo_public_safety_office_19.html|title=Kalamazoo Public Safety officers target black drivers in traffic stops, racial profiling study concludes|publisher=MLive.com|accessdate=15 April 2020|date=3 September 2013|last=Hall, Jr|first=Rex|work=Kalamazoo Gazette}}</ref>  Since this time the department has been working hard to confront the racial bias in its department and has received international news coverage for attempting to address the racial issues the department acknowledges it has.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/watch/shows/america-tonight/articles/2015/2/23/kalamazoo-police.html|title=Kalamazoo Police Tackle Racial Profiling|work=Al Jazeera America|publisher=aljazeera.com|accessdate=30 May 2015|date=23 February 2020|last=Amin|first=Sameen}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\nOn April 18, 2011, while responding to a shots fired call in Kalamazoo's Edison neighborhood, PSO Eric Zapata was fatally shot. Officer Zapata was the first officer in Kalamazoo to be killed in the line of duty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2012/04/a_year_after_the_death_of_eric.html|title=Officer Eric Zapata remembered: Fellow Kalamazoo officers recall the night he died (Part 1 of 2)|work=MLive.com|accessdate=28 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EW6mPOSX1Ko Kalamazoo Public Safety Promotional Video]\n\n{{Michigan fire departments}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalamazoo Department Of Public Safety}}\n[[Category:Municipal police departments of Michigan]]\n[[Category:Fire departments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Kalamazoo, Michigan]]\n[[Category:1983 establishments in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "C.Fred", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublic Safety model:not a proper noun", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalamazoo_Department_of_Public_Safety"}
{"title_page": "Roma Potiki", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand M\u0101ori poet, playwright, performer, and commentator on M\u0101ori theatre}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Roma Potiki\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1958|02|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Lower Hutt]], New Zealand\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| field = poetry, theatre commentary, theatre, visual arts\n| training = \n| movement = \n| works = \n| patrons = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| elected = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Roma Potiki''' (born 1958<ref>{{Cite book|title=Toi te Ao : Aotearoa world celebration of indigenous art and history, Te Taumata Gallery, Auckland, 1993.|last=|first=|date=1993|publisher=Toi Te Ao Art Committee|isbn=0473023113|location=Wellington [N.Z.]|pages=32|oclc=154557391}}</ref>) is a New Zealand poet, playwright, visual artist, curator, theatre actor and director, as well as a commentator on M\u0101ori theatre.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Oxford companion to New Zealand literature|last=|first=|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0195583485|editor-last=Robinson|editor-first=Roger|location=Melbourne, Victoria.|pages=448\u2013449|oclc=40598609|editor-last2=Wattie|editor-first2=Nelson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=World theories of theatre|last=Odom|first=Glenn A.|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2017|isbn=9781317586289|location=London|pages=216\u2013218|oclc=988290202}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Decolonizing the stage : theatrical syncretism and post-colonial drama|last=Balme|first=Christopher B.|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1999|isbn=0198184441|location=Oxford|pages=64\u201365|oclc=39655593}}</ref> She is of [[Te Rarawa]], [[Te Aup\u014duri]] and [[Ngati Rangitihi]] descent.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.komako.org.nz/person/822|title=Roma Potiki|last=Underhill|first=Bridget|date=|website=www.komako.org.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> As well as being a published poet, her work is included in the permanent collection of the [[Dowse Art Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.read-nz.org/writer/potiki-roma|title=Potiki, Roma|last=|first=|date=January 2017|website=www.read-nz.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nRoma Potiki was born in [[Lower Hutt]], a city in the Wellington Region, and grew up in the suburb [[Wainuiomata]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/roma-potiki|title=Roma Potiki|last=Foundation|first=Poetry|date=2019-11-15|website=Poetry Foundation|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> As a child she attended Wainuiomata Primary School, Woodhatton Primary School, Wainuiomata College and Wellington High School.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.komako.org.nz/person/822|title=K\u014dmako A bibliography of writing by M\u0101ori in English|last=|first=|date=2019-11-15|website=www.komako.org.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109015120/https://www.komako.org.nz/person/822|archive-date=2019-11-09|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> Her first play was written while at primary school and she also started writing poetry at school.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nRoma Potiki was involved in contemporary M\u0101ori theatre in early formative years. She was in a play performed by Te Ika A Maui Players in 1978 called Death of the Land by Rore Hapipi's (Rowley Habib).<ref name=\":1\" /> She went on to help form the M\u0101ori theatre company Maranga Mai in 1979.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/maori-theatre-te-whare-tapere-hou/page-2|title=2. \u2013 M\u0101ori theatre - te whare tapere h\u014du \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand|last=Taonga|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|website=teara.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref> This company was linked to the [[M\u0101ori protest movement]] and they toured a theatre production in 1979 - 1980 to marae and schools.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1990 she was a founding director of another theatre company He Ara Hou. They performed and toured a play called ''Whatungarongaro.''<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> This play was directed by Potiki and John Anderson and devised over nine months with the company members. Potiki had previously done workshops with a theatre company PETA (Philippines Educational Theatre Association) and was influenced by their way of working.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Performing Aotearoa : New Zealand theatre and drama in an age of transition|last=O'Donnell|first=David|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-359-6|editor-last=Maufort|editor-first=Marc|location=Bruxelles|pages=271|chapter=Calming the Oceans: Interview with Briar Grace-Smith|oclc=165412282|editor-last2=O'Donnell|editor-first2=David}}</ref>\n\nRoma Potiki's writing includes poetry contribution to many anthologies, as well as published volumes. She has written the forward to books of New Zealand M\u0101ori plays and contributed text to exhibition catalogues. As a fine artist Potiki has exhibited art work and one of her pieces ''Hinewai'' is in the collection of the [[Dowse Art Museum]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe poem ''Stones in her Mouth'' by Potiki inspired contemporary New Zealand choreographer [[Lemi Ponifasio]] to create a community leadership project also called ''[https://www.redcat.org/event/lemi-ponifasio-mau-stones Stones in her Mouth]'' in 2013. This involved a group of M\u0101ori women holding workshops at marae and writing text that was then performed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Floating Islanders : Pasifika theatre in Aotearoa|last=Warrington, Lisa|publisher=|others=O'Donnell, David, 1956-|year=2017|isbn=978-1-988531-07-6|location=Dunedin, New Zealand|pages=139|oclc=994638351}}</ref>\n\n==== He Ara Hou and Whatungarongaro ====\nBefore actor [[Rena Owen]] was in ''[[Once Were Warriors (film)|Once Were Warriors]]'' she performed a similar role in theatre company He Ara Hou's play ''Whatungarongaro'' that Potiki a co-creator of. Owens performance in ''Whatungarongaro'' influenced her being cast in Once Were Warriors.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Performing Aotearoa : New Zealand theatre and drama in an age of transition|last=Edmond|first=Murray|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-359-6|editor-last=Maufort|editor-first=Marc|location=Bruxelles|pages=65|chapter=\"Autonomous Theatre\" in New Zealand|oclc=165412282|editor-last2=O'Donnell|editor-first2=David}}</ref>\n\nPlaywright and director of theatre company Tawata Productions [[Hone Kouka]] cites seeing ''Whatungarongaro'' in 1991 at the Depot Theatre in Wellington as being life changing and convincing him that innovative M\u0101ori theatre had no boundaries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Performing Aotearoa : New Zealand theatre and drama in an age of transition|last=Kouka|first=Hone|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-359-6|editor-last=Maufort|editor-first=Marc|location=Bruxelles|pages=240|chapter=The State of Contemporary Theatre|oclc=165412282|editor-last2=O'Donnell|editor-first2=David}}</ref> Another New Zealand theatre and film writer [[Briar Grace-Smith]] was an assistant to Potiki and learnt from the process of making ''Whatungarongaro''.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Published works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n\n*''Stones in Her Mouth'' ''(1992)''<ref name=\":0\" /> Publisher: Tamakimakaurau, N.Z. IWA<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.library.auckland.ac.nz/search/roma%20potiki|title=The University of Auckland Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Roma Potiki (1995)'' Publisher: Wai-te-ata Press, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Shaking the Tree'' ''(1998)''<ref name=\":0\" /> Publisher: Steele Roberts, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Oriori: a M\u0101ori Child is Born: From Conception to Birth'' (1999)<ref name=\":0\" /> co-authored with [[Robyn Kahukiwa]]. Publisher: Wai-te-ata Press, Wellington, NZ\n\n=== Plays ===\n\n*''Whatungarongaro'' ''(1990)'' Roma Potiki and He Ara Hou. Published in ''Ta Matou Mangai: Three Plays of the 1990s: Irirangi Bay, Taku Mangai, Whatungarongaro (1999)'' ed. [[Hone Kouka]]. Publisher: Victoria University Press, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Going Home (1996)<ref name=\":0\" />''\n\n=== Other ===\n\n*Introduction - ''He Reo Hou: 5 Plays by M\u0101ori playwrights'' ''(1991)'' ed. Simon Garrett. Publisher: Playmarket, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Robyn Kahukiwa : Works from 1985 - 1995 (1995)'' Exhibition catalogue. Includes essays by Anne Kirker and Jonathan Man\u00e9-Wheoki, and an interview by Roma Potiki. Publisher: Bowen Galleries, Wellington N.Z.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*Foreword - ''Waiora'' ''(1997)'' by [[Hone Kouka]]\n*''Memory Walking (1998)'' \"Exhibition of contemporary paintings, prints and installation work by eight women artists from around the world.\" Text by Roma Potiki. Exhibiting artists: Lubaina Himid, Michi itami, Robyn Kahukiwa, Jean LaMarr, Lily Laita, Debra Priestly, Maud Sulter, Judy Watson. Publisher: City Gallery, Wellington N.Z.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Anthologies ===\nRoma Potiki is widely published in anthologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.read-nz.org/writer/potiki-roma|title=Read NZ|last=|first=|date=|website=www.read-nz.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109015119/https://www.read-nz.org/writer/potiki-roma|archive-date=2019-11-09|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nSelected list:\n\n*''Te Ao Marama: Vol 4: Contemporary Maori Writing for Children (1994)'' ed. [[Witi Ihimaera]]\n*''Oxford (1997)''\n*''My Heart Goes Swimming : New Zealand Love Poems (2000)'' ed. [[Jenny Bornholdt]], [[Gregory O'Brien]]\n*''Mauri Ola: Contemporary Polynesian Poems in English'' ''(2010)'' Ed. [[Albert Wendt]], Reina Whaitiri and [[Robert Sullivan (poet)|Robert Sullivan]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [https://researcharchive.vuw.ac.nz/xmlui/handle/10063/995 Calling the Taniwha: Mana Wahine Maori and the Poetry of Roma Potiki], a research paper about Roma Potiki's poetry by Kelly Lambert.\n* [https://teara.govt.nz/en/maori-theatre-te-whare-tapere-hou/page-2 First M\u0101ori theatre companies, 1970\u20131990]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Potiki, Roma}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women artists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:New Zealand stage actresses]]\n[[Category:New Zealand theatre directors]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women poets]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women curators]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Hutt]]\n[[Category:Te Rarawa]]\n[[Category:Te Aup\u014duri]]\n[[Category:Ng\u0101ti Rangitihi]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand M\u0101ori poet, playwright, performer and commentator on M\u0101ori theatre}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Roma Potiki\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1958|02|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Lower Hutt]], New Zealand\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| field = poetry, theatre commentary, theatre, visual arts\n| training = \n| movement = \n| works = \n| patrons = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| elected = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Roma Potiki''' (born 1958<ref>{{Cite book|title=Toi te Ao : Aotearoa world celebration of indigenous art and history, Te Taumata Gallery, Auckland, 1993.|last=|first=|date=1993|publisher=Toi Te Ao Art Committee|isbn=0473023113|location=Wellington [N.Z.]|pages=32|oclc=154557391}}</ref>) is a New Zealand poet, playwright, visual artist, curator, theatre actor and director, as well as a commentator on M\u0101ori theatre.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Oxford companion to New Zealand literature|last=|first=|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0195583485|editor-last=Robinson|editor-first=Roger|location=Melbourne, Victoria.|pages=448\u2013449|oclc=40598609|editor-last2=Wattie|editor-first2=Nelson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=World theories of theatre|last=Odom|first=Glenn A.|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2017|isbn=9781317586289|location=London|pages=216\u2013218|oclc=988290202}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Decolonizing the stage : theatrical syncretism and post-colonial drama|last=Balme|first=Christopher B.|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1999|isbn=0198184441|location=Oxford|pages=64\u201365|oclc=39655593}}</ref> She is of [[Te Rarawa]], [[Te Aup\u014duri]] and [[Ngati Rangitihi]] descent.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.komako.org.nz/person/822|title=Roma Potiki|last=Underhill|first=Bridget|date=|website=www.komako.org.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> As well as being a published poet, her work is included in the permanent collection of the [[Dowse Art Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.read-nz.org/writer/potiki-roma|title=Potiki, Roma|last=|first=|date=January 2017|website=www.read-nz.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nRoma Potiki was born in [[Lower Hutt]], a city in the Wellington Region, and grew up in the suburb [[Wainuiomata]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/roma-potiki|title=Roma Potiki|last=Foundation|first=Poetry|date=2019-11-15|website=Poetry Foundation|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> As a child she attended Wainuiomata Primary School, Woodhatton Primary School, Wainuiomata College and Wellington High School.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.komako.org.nz/person/822|title=K\u014dmako A bibliography of writing by M\u0101ori in English|last=|first=|date=2019-11-15|website=www.komako.org.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109015120/https://www.komako.org.nz/person/822|archive-date=2019-11-09|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> Her first play was written while at primary school and she also started writing poetry at school.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nRoma Potiki was involved in contemporary M\u0101ori theatre in early formative years. She was in a play performed by Te Ika A Maui Players in 1978 called Death of the Land by Rore Hapipi's (Rowley Habib).<ref name=\":1\" /> She went on to help form the M\u0101ori theatre company Maranga Mai in 1979.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/maori-theatre-te-whare-tapere-hou/page-2|title=2. \u2013 M\u0101ori theatre - te whare tapere h\u014du \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand|last=Taonga|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|website=teara.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref> This company was linked to the [[M\u0101ori protest movement]] and they toured a theatre production in 1979 - 1980 to marae and schools.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1990 she was a founding director of another theatre company He Ara Hou. They performed and toured a play called ''Whatungarongaro.''<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> This play was directed by Potiki and John Anderson and devised over nine months with the company members. Potiki had previously done workshops with a theatre company PETA (Philippines Educational Theatre Association) and was influenced by their way of working.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Performing Aotearoa : New Zealand theatre and drama in an age of transition|last=O'Donnell|first=David|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-359-6|editor-last=Maufort|editor-first=Marc|location=Bruxelles|pages=271|chapter=Calming the Oceans: Interview with Briar Grace-Smith|oclc=165412282|editor-last2=O'Donnell|editor-first2=David}}</ref>\n\nRoma Potiki's writing includes poetry contribution to many anthologies, as well as published volumes. She has written the forward to books of New Zealand M\u0101ori plays and contributed text to exhibition catalogues. As a fine artist Potiki has exhibited art work and one of her pieces ''Hinewai'' is in the collection of the [[Dowse Art Museum]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe poem ''Stones in her Mouth'' by Potiki inspired contemporary New Zealand choreographer [[Lemi Ponifasio]] to create a community leadership project also called ''[https://www.redcat.org/event/lemi-ponifasio-mau-stones Stones in her Mouth]'' in 2013. This involved a group of M\u0101ori women holding workshops at marae and writing text that was then performed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Floating Islanders : Pasifika theatre in Aotearoa|last=Warrington, Lisa|publisher=|others=O'Donnell, David, 1956-|year=2017|isbn=978-1-988531-07-6|location=Dunedin, New Zealand|pages=139|oclc=994638351}}</ref>\n\n==== He Ara Hou and Whatungarongaro ====\nBefore actor [[Rena Owen]] was in ''[[Once Were Warriors (film)|Once Were Warriors]]'' she performed a similar role in theatre company He Ara Hou's play ''Whatungarongaro'' that Potiki a co-creator of. Owens performance in ''Whatungarongaro'' influenced her being cast in Once Were Warriors.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Performing Aotearoa : New Zealand theatre and drama in an age of transition|last=Edmond|first=Murray|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-359-6|editor-last=Maufort|editor-first=Marc|location=Bruxelles|pages=65|chapter=\"Autonomous Theatre\" in New Zealand|oclc=165412282|editor-last2=O'Donnell|editor-first2=David}}</ref> \n\nPlaywright and director of theatre company Tawata Productions [[Hone Kouka]] cites seeing ''Whatungarongaro'' in 1991 at the Depot Theatre in Wellington as being life changing and convincing him that innovative M\u0101ori theatre had no boundaries.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Performing Aotearoa : New Zealand theatre and drama in an age of transition|last=Kouka|first=Hone|date=2007|publisher=P.I.E. Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-359-6|editor-last=Maufort|editor-first=Marc|location=Bruxelles|pages=240|chapter=The State of Contemporary Theatre|oclc=165412282|editor-last2=O'Donnell|editor-first2=David}}</ref> Another New Zealand theatre and film writer [[Briar Grace-Smith]] was an assistant to Potiki and learnt from the process of making ''Whatungarongaro''.<ref name=\":5\" />     \n\n== Published Works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n\n*''Stones in Her Mouth'' ''(1992)''<ref name=\":0\" /> Publisher: Tamakimakaurau, N.Z. IWA<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.library.auckland.ac.nz/search/roma%20potiki|title=The University of Auckland Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*''Roma Potiki (1995)'' Publisher: Wai-te-ata Press, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Shaking the Tree'' ''(1998)''<ref name=\":0\" /> Publisher: Steele Roberts, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Oriori: a M\u0101ori Child is Born: From Conception to Birth'' (1999)<ref name=\":0\" /> co-authored with [[Robyn Kahukiwa]]. Publisher: Wai-te-ata Press, Wellington, NZ\n\n=== Plays ===\n\n*''Whatungarongaro'' ''(1990)'' Roma Potiki and He Ara Hou. Published in ''Ta Matou Mangai: Three Plays of the 1990s: Irirangi Bay, Taku Mangai, Whatungarongaro (1999)'' ed. [[Hone Kouka]]. Publisher: Victoria University Press, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Going Home (1996)<ref name=\":0\" />''\n\n=== Other ===\n\n*Introduction - ''He Reo Hou: 5 Plays by M\u0101ori playwrights'' ''(1991)'' ed. Simon Garrett. Publisher: Playmarket, Wellington, N.Z.\n*''Robyn Kahukiwa : Works from 1985 - 1995 (1995)'' Exhibition catalogue. Includes essays by Anne Kirker and Jonathan Man\u00e9-Wheoki, and an interview by Roma Potiki. Publisher: Bowen Galleries, Wellington N.Z. <ref name=\":2\" />\n*Foreward - ''Waiora'' ''(1997)'' by [[Hone Kouka]]\n*''Memory Walking (1998)'' \"Exhibition of contemporary paintings, prints and installation work by eight women artists from around the world.\" Text by Roma Potiki. Exhibiting artists: Lubaina Himid, Michi itami, Robyn Kahukiwa, Jean LaMarr, Lily Laita, Debra Priestly, Maud Sulter, Judy Watson. Publisher: City Gallery, Wellington N.Z.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Anthologies ===\nRoma Potiki is widely published in anthologies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.read-nz.org/writer/potiki-roma|title=Read NZ|last=|first=|date=|website=www.read-nz.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109015119/https://www.read-nz.org/writer/potiki-roma|archive-date=2019-11-09|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> \n\nSelected list:\n\n*''Te Ao Marama: Vol 4: Contemporary Maori Writing for Children (1994)'' ed. [[Witi Ihimaera]]\n*''Oxford (1997)''\n*''My Heart Goes Swimming : New Zealand Love Poems (2000)'' ed. [[Jenny Bornholdt]], [[Gregory O'Brien]]\n*''Mauri Ola: Contemporary Polynesian Poems in English'' ''(2010)'' Ed. [[Albert Wendt]], Reina Whaitiri and [[Robert Sullivan (poet)|Robert Sullivan]]\n\n== Further reading ==\nThere is a published Masters research paper about Roma Potiki's poetry by Kelly Lambert.\n\n* [https://researcharchive.vuw.ac.nz/xmlui/handle/10063/995 Calling the Taniwha: Mana Wahine Maori and the Poetry of Roma Potiki] \n\nTe Ara, The New Zealand Encyclopedia has some information about background to M\u0101ori Theatre. \n\n* [https://teara.govt.nz/en/maori-theatre-te-whare-tapere-hou/page-2 First M\u0101ori theatre companies, 1970\u20131990]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Potiki, Roma}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category: