{"title_page": "Harrison Afful", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Harrison Afful\n| image = 20150331 Mali vs Ghana 126.jpg\n| caption = Harrison with Ghana in 2015\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Tema]], [[Greater Accra Region|Greater Accra]], Ghana\n| height = 1.68 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Fullback]]\n| currentclub = [[Columbus Crew SC]]\n| clubnumber = 25\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]]\n| years1 = 2005\u20132009\n| clubs1 = [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]]\n| caps1 = 148\n| goals1 = 11\n| years2 = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Asante Kotoko S.C.|Asante Kotoko]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 68\n| goals2 = 5\n| years3 = 2009\u20132015\n| clubs3 = [[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis|ES Tunis]]\n| caps3 = 118\n| goals3 = 11\n| years4 = 2015\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Columbus Crew SC]]\n| caps4 = 118\n| goals4 = 5\n| nationalyears1 = 2006\n| nationalteam1 = [[Ghana national under-20 football team|Ghana U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2008\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 84\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Team|{{fb|Ghana}}}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]|[[2008 Africa Cup of Nations|2008]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]|[[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]|[[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]]}}\n| pcupdate = 1 March 2020\n| ntupdate = 18 November 2018\n}}\n\n'''Harrison Afful''' (born 24 July 1986), commonly [[Mononymous person|known simply as]] '''Harrison''', is a Ghanaian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|fullback]] for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Columbus Crew SC]] and the [[Ghana national football team|Ghanaian national team]]. He appeared previously for [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]] and [[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis|ES Tunis]] and spent time on loan to [[Asante Kotoko S.C.|Asante Kotoko]].\n\nHarrison came through the youth setup at the [[West African Football Academy|Feyenoord Academy]], spending his first two professional seasons on the Academy's senior team. He then moved on loan to Asante Kotoko, spending two seasons with the Porcupines and winning the [[Ghana Premier League]] in 2008. After four years of professional football, Harrison left Ghana for the first time to join ES Tunis of the [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1]]. He played the next six seasons with Tunis, appearing for the club more than 170 times. Tunis won four league titles during Harrison's time there, appeared in three [[CAF Champions League]] finals, and won the [[2011 CAF Champions League Final]]; Harrison scored the only goal over the two legs. In the summer of 2015, Harrison moved to the United States and signed for Columbus Crew SC, helping the club reach [[MLS Cup 2015]] in his first season.\n\nAt the international level, Harrison made his Ghanaian debut at the [[2008 Africa Cup of Nations]], helping Ghana to a third-place finish at that tournament. He has since appeared for the [[Ghana national football team|Black Stars]] at four more AFCON tournaments, finishing as runners-up in [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]] and [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]]. He was called up to Ghana's squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], appearing twice during the tournament. Harrison captained his nation for the first time in a [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly]] against [[Congo national football team|Congo]] on 1 September 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Tema]], Harrison grew up {{convert|23|km|abbr=off}} away in [[Nungua]], Ghana. He used to watch the Ghana national team on television with his family before becoming a professional footballer.<ref name=Story>{{cite web |url=https://footballghana.com/even-if-i-get-one-minute-to-play-i-will-make-use-of-it-harrison-affuls-world-cup-story |title=\"Even if I get one minute to play, I will make use of it.\"- Harrison Afful's World Cup story |website=FootballGhana.com |publisher=Football Ghana |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Feyenoord Academy===\nHarrison joined the [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]] after being discovered as a youth by [[Sam Arday]] and went on to spend four years with the senior team.<ref>{{cite web |last=Abayateye |first=Michael |url=https://www.primenewsghana.com/sports/harrison-afful-s-tribute-to-sam-ardey.html |title=Harrison Afful\u2019s tribute to Sam Arday |website=PrimeNewsGhana.com |publisher=Prime Network Ltd. |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=13 February 2017}}</ref> Although he spent two of those seasons on loan to [[Asante Kotoko S.C.]], Harrison appeared 148 times in total and scored 11 goals for the Academy. In 2008, he went on a trial with the Academy's parent club, [[Feyenoord]]. He was linked with a move to [[F.C. Copenhagen|K\u00f8benhavn]] but was told that he was too small and returned to Ghana.<ref name=Story/> He also spent time training with [[Helsingborgs IF|Helsingborgs]] in December of that year but failed to land a deal after suffering a [[hamstring injury]] while he was in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/content/view/2222/51/ |title=Afful fails to land Sweden deal |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |date=11 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818234752/http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/content/view/2222/51/ |archivedate=18 August 2009 |access-date=27 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Asante Kotoko====\nHarrison joined Asante Kotoko on loan at the start of the 2007 season, the first time he had played at a club other than the Feyenoord Academy. The loan move was made possible through a clause in [[Jordan Opoku]]'s contract. He had been bought by Asante Kotoko the year before, and his contract allowed Kotoko to choose one player to bring in on loan from the Academy. They exercised it by choosing Harrison.<ref name=Osmaninterview>{{cite web |last=Osman |first=Rahman |url=http://sport.citifmonline.com/2015/07/07/harrison-afful-small-man-huge-drive-and-passion/ |title=Harrison Afful: Small man, huge drive and passion |website=CitiFMOnline.com |publisher=Citi Newsroom |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nKotoko head coach Bashiru Hayford handed Harrison his debut with a 10-minute cameo in a friendly match. This allowed the defender to break into the first team after initially appearing to be outside Hayford's plans.<ref name=Osmaninterview/> Harrison went on to spend two seasons on loan to Kotoko. He scored five goals in 68 appearances during his time at the club, winning the [[Ghana Premier League]] in 2008, and was named the league's Player of the Year that season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.remingtonellis.com/players/harrisonafful/ |title=Harrison Afful at Remington Ellis Management |website=RemingtonEllis.com |publisher=Remington Ellis Management Group |accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref> He also made his national team debut while at Kotoko.<ref name=Story/>\n\n===ES Tunis===\n====2009\u20132010: Early career in Tunisia====\nOn 25 August 2009, Harrison officially signed a three-year contract with [[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis]] (EST). He had trained with the club prior to the announcement and had scored a goal in a friendly match, helping convince Tunis to complete the signing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/10609/esperance-sign-afful.php |title=Esperance sign Afful |website=Kickoff.com |publisher=[[Kick Off (magazine)|KICK OFF magazine]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=25 August 2009}}</ref> The move to the [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1]] side marked the first time Harrison had signed for a club outside Ghana. He made his debut for EST on 12 September, playing the full 90 minutes in a 4\u20130 victory over [[CS Sfaxien]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/report/ligue-1-2009-2010-esperance-tunis-club-sportif-sfaxien/ |title=ES Tunis 4\u20130 CS Sfaxien |website=WorldFootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL Medien GmbH & Co. KG |accessdate=21 December 2018 |date=12 September 2009}}</ref> Harrison scored his first two goals for the club in a three-round span in the spring of 2010, tallying against [[CA Bizertin]] on 28 April and [[ES Hammam-Sousse]] on 15 May.<ref name=WFprofile>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/harrison-afful/2/ |title=Harrison Afful at WorldFootball.net |website=WorldFootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL Medien GmbH & Co. KG |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> He finished the season with two goals from 18 appearances as Tunis claimed their second consecutive CLP-1 title.<ref name=TunisHonors>{{cite web |url=http://www.est.org.tn/palmares-foot.php |title=ES Tunis \u2013 Palmar\u00e8s Football |website=EST.org.tn |publisher=Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis |accessdate=19 December 2018 |language=French |trans-title=ES Tunis \u2013 Football Honors}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u20132013: Champions League success====\nIn his [[2010\u201311 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|second season]] at ES Tunis, Harrison did not play a large role in league play. He appeared 17 times without a goal as the Blood and Gold claimed their third consecutive league title.<ref name=TunisHonors/> Instead, he became a fixture in the Tunis squad in [[2010 CAF Champions League|CAF Champions League]] play. Harrison made his debut in the tournament on 16 July 2010, appearing in Group A play against [[ES S\u00e9tif]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2010/07/16/africa/caf-champions-league/entente-sportive-de-setif/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/935532/ |title=ES S\u00e9tif 0\u20131 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=16 July 2010}}</ref> He went on to appear in every game of the tournament from the group stage on, helping lead EST to the [[2010 CAF Champions League Final]]. Against [[TP Mazembe]] in the final, Harrison played 90 minutes in the first leg in a 5\u20130 defeat for Tunis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafonline.com/competition/champions-league_2010/news/6994-mazembe-move-within-touching-distance.html |title=Mazembe move within touching distance |website=CAFOnline.com |publisher=[[Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Africaine de Football]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=31 October 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918022832/http://www.cafonline.com/competition/champions-league_2010/news/6994-mazembe-move-within-touching-distance.html |archivedate=18 September 2012}}</ref> He scored in the 24th minute of the second leg, his first-ever goal in the competition, but Tunis could only manage a 1\u20131 draw and were defeated on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/9187255.stm |title=TP Mazembe claim African Champions League crown again |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=13 November 2010}}</ref> On the season, Harrison appeared 27 times in all competitions and scored once.\n\n[[File:Harrison Afful.jpg|thumb|230px|right|Harrison scored twice in five [[CAF Champions League]] Final appearances with Tunis.]]\nJust as in the prior season, Harrison played sparingly in the CLP-1, failing to make a league appearance until ES Tunis had concluded their Champions League run. He appeared in 16 league matches without scoring as Tunis rolled to a fourth consecutive league crown.<ref name=TunisHonors/> In [[2011 CAF Champions League|CAF Champions League]] play, Harrison again played a headlining role once the group stage began as Tunis eliminated [[Al-Hilal Club (Omdurman)|Al-Hilal]] in the semifinals and advanced to the continental final for the second consecutive year. He came off the bench in the first leg of the [[2011 CAF Champions League Final]], replacing [[Wajdi Bouazzi]] in the 90th minute of a draw with [[Wydad AC|Wydad Casablanca]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2011/11/06/africa/caf-champions-league/wydad-athletic-club/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1219381/ |title=Wydad Casablanca 0\u20130 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=6 November 2011}}</ref> Harrison started in the second leg, playing at right back at the [[Stade 7 November]]. In the 22nd minute, he placed a left-footed, curling shot into the upper corner, a goal that gave Tunis a 1\u20130 lead on the night and eventually the second Champions League title in club history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/15708355 |title=Esperance crowned African champions with win over Wydad |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=12 November 2011}}</ref> Harrison would later rate that goal as his favorite soccer memory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/players/harrison-afful |title=Harrison Afful \u2013 Columbus Crew SC profile |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=[[Columbus Crew SC]] |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> By virtue of winning the Champions League, Tunis qualified for the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup]]; Harrison appeared off the bench in the quarterfinals against [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=257429/match=300180904/report.html |title=ES Tunis 1\u20132 Al Sadd |website=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=11 December 2011}}</ref> and started the fifth place match against [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=257441/match=300180903/report.html |title=Monterrey 3\u20132 ES Tunis |website=FIFA.com |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=14 December 2011}}</ref> On the season, he played 29 times in all competitions, scoring once.\n\nAlthough Harrison's contract with ES Tunis expired at the end of June, he re-signed with the club on 2 July 2012, inking a three-year contract extension that ran through the end of June 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/harrison-afful-signs-new-esperance-deal-2 |title=Harrison Afful signs new Esperance deal |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=2 July 2012}}</ref> With his contract situation resolved, he found his scoring boots in CLP-1 play, scoring goals against [[ES Zarzis]] on 21 November,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/11/21/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/esperance-sportive-de-zarzis/1403708/ |title=ES Tunis 2\u20131 ES Zarzis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=21 November 2012}}</ref> [[JS Kairouan]] on 8 December,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/12/08/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/js-kairouanaise/1403721/ |title=ES Tunis 5\u20131 JS Kairouan |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=8 December 2012}}</ref> and [[Club Africain]] on 31 March<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/03/31/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/club-africain/1465991/ |title=ES Tunis 3\u20131 Club Africain |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=31 March 2013}}</ref> \u2014 all matches that ended in victories for Tunis. Harrison again played a vital role for EST in the [[2012 CAF Champions League|Champions League]]. He helped the Blood and Gold eliminate Mazembe in the semifinals and advance to their third consecutive final to take on [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]]. He played 73 minutes in the first leg of the [[2012 CAF Champions League Final]], helping Tunis earn a 1\u20131 draw<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/11/04/africa/caf-champions-league/al-ahly/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1284936/ |title=Al Ahly 1\u20131 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=4 November 2012}}</ref> but was suspended for the second leg due to [[Penalty card#Yellow card|yellow card]] accumulation<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Afful-suspended-for-Champions-League-final-255407?channel=D1 |title=Afful suspended for Champions League final |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=GhanaWeb |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=5 November 2012}}</ref> as Tunis were defeated by a 3\u20132 aggregate scoreline.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/harrison-afful-and-esperance-miss-out-on-caf-champions-league-trophy?replytocom=176631 |title=Harrison Afful and Esperance miss out on CAF Champions League trophy |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=17 November 2012}}</ref> Harrison appeared 28 times in all competitions on the campaign, scoring three goals.\n\n====2013\u20132015: Final seasons at EST====\n[[2013\u201314 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2013\u201314]] would turn out to be the busiest and most prolific season of Harrison's career to date. He appeared in a career-high 37 matches in all competitions and scored four goals. In CLP-1 play, he scored twice before the turn of the year, tallying against [[Stade Tunisien]] on 3 November<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/11/03/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/stade-tunisien/1551406/ |title=ES Tunis 5\u20130 Stade Tunisien |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=3 November 2013}}</ref> and [[LPS Tozeur]] on 25 December.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/12/25/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/lp-tozeur-avenir/1551456/ |title=ES Tunis 4\u20130 LPS Tozeur |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=25 December 2013}}</ref> He continued his form after new head coach [[Ruud Krol]] was hired, scoring in the return fixture against Tunisien on 15 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/02/15/tunisia/ligue-1/stade-tunisien/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1644989/ |title=Stade Tunisien 0\u20132 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=15 February 2014}}</ref> He tallyed the game-winning goal against Sfaxien on 2 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/04/02/tunisia/ligue-1/club-sportif-sfaxien/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1645020/ |title=CS Sfaxien 0\u20131 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=2 April 2014}}</ref> as Tunis claimed their fourth league title in Harrison's five seasons at the club.<ref name=TunisHonors/> He added ten more appearances in the [[2013 CAF Champions League|Champions League]], but EST were defeated by [[Orlando Pirates F.C.|Orlando Pirates]] in the semifinals and denied a fourth consecutive trip to the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/10/19/africa/caf-champions-league/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/orlando-pirates/1473572/ |title=Orlando Pirates 1\u20131 ES Tunis (1\u20131 agg.) |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Harrison was the subject of transfer interest, with reports from his native Ghana claiming that he was the subject of an offer from [[Olympique de Marseille]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Marseille-make-offer-to-sign-Harrison-Afful-306438 |title=Marseille make offer to sign Harrison Afful |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=GhanaWeb |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=16 April 2014}}</ref> The [[Ligue 1]] club were reportedly looking to sign Harrison before the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] began, in an effort to keep down the player's price. Following the domestic season, however, ES Tunis announced that Harrison would not leave the club until after the World Cup at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web |last=Talaat |first=Tarek |url=https://www.supersport.com/football/africa/news/140501/Harrison_Afful_to_stay_at_Esperance |title=Harrison Afful to stay at Esperance |website=[[SuperSport.com]] |publisher=MultiChoice Ltd. |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> He continued to attract interest after the World Cup, with a reported 13 European clubs battling for his signature;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-defender-harrison-afful-attracts-13-offers-europe-excellent-world-cup?comment=1 |title=Ghana defender Harrison Afful attracts 13 offers from Europe after excellent World Cup |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=11 July 2014}}</ref> however, it was [[Al Wahda FC|Al Wahda]], of the United Arab Emirates, who had reportedly won the race for the defender. Harrison underwent a medical with the Clarets, but the club canceled the deal after ES Tunis broke off communication and he thus returned to Tunisia.<ref>{{cite web |last=Passela |first=Amith |url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/al-wahda-break-off-deal-for-ghana-s-harrison-afful-1.2849?videoId=5612976228001 |title=Al Wahda break off deal for Ghana\u2019s Harrison Afful |website=TheNational.ae |publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter any potential move in the summer fell through, Harrison returned to Tunis to begin the [[2014\u201315 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2014\u201315 season]]. On 31 August, in a match away to Bizertin, he scored two goals to help EST claim a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanastar.com/sports/ghanaian-defender-harrison-afful-hits-brace-for-esperance-de-tunis/ |title=Ghanaian Defender Harrison Afful Hits Brace for Esperance de Tunis |website=GhanaStar.com |publisher=Ghana Star |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=1 September 2014}}</ref> Harrison would not score again for the remainder of the league's season as Esp\u00e9rance placed third in the CLP-1, their lowest league finish during Harrison's time at the club. In [[2014 CAF Champions League]] play, he scored in both the first and second qualifying rounds, helping Tunis advance over [[Gor Mahia F.C.|Gor Mahia]] and [[AS Real Bamako|Real Bamako]], respectively.<ref name=\"sw\">{{Soccerway|harrison-afful/21414}}</ref> EST were eliminated in the group stage, however, the first time they had failed to advance to the knockout rounds since Harrison had joined the club. He finished the season with 29 appearances in all competitions, scoring four goals.\n\nWith his contract set to expire at the end of June, Harrison was rumored to be re-signing a two-year deal with the Blood and Gold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/soccer_transfers/Harrison-Afful-to-extend-Esperance-contract-359987?channel=D1 |title=Harrison Afful to extend Esperance contract |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=28 May 2015}}</ref> In the final month of his contract, he appeared four times and scored a goal for Tunis in continental competitions. However, Harrison and the club could not agree on a contract, and he departed after more than six seasons with Tunis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Afful-leaves-Esperance-after-six-seasons-366062 |title=Afful leaves Esperance after six seasons |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=2 July 2015}}</ref> Harrison appeared 172 times and scored 16 goals for Esperance.\n\n====FIFA case====\nFollowing his departure from Tunis at the end of June 2015, Harrison was reportedly not paid the remaining salaries and bonuses owed to him by the club. He filed a case with [[FIFA]] over the issue, and in May 2016 the organization sided with Harrison in the case. FIFA ordered Esp\u00e9rance to pay the remaining monies within one month of the ruling date; if they failed to do so, they would be docked six points in league play. FIFA also ruled that if the debts persisted, Tunis would be relegated to the [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 2]]. The club also paid a fine \"in the tens of thousands of Swiss francs to FIFA\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/FIFA-orders-Esperance-to-pay-Harrison-Afful-442587 |title=FIFA orders Esperance to pay Harrison Afful |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Columbus Crew SC===\n====2015\u20132016: Initial years in Columbus====\nAfter his contract with Tunis expired at the end of June, Harrison joined [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Columbus Crew SC]] as a Discovery Signing.<ref>{{cite web |author=Crew SC Communications |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2015/07/30/crew-sc-signs-defender-harrison-afful |title=Crew SC signs defender Harrison Afful |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=30 July 2015}}</ref> Although the transfer was announced on 30 July 2015, he was only added to the roster after securing his visa and thus had to wait to make his club debut until 19 August. He started a 2\u20132 draw with [[New York City FC]], playing 60 minutes before being replaced by [[Hector Jim\u00e9nez (soccer)|Hector Jim\u00e9nez]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2015-08-19-columbus-crew-sc-vs-new-york-city-fc/boxscore |title=Columbus Crew SC 2\u20132 New York City FC |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=19 August 2015}}</ref> Harrison missed several matches while on international duty<ref>{{cite web |last=Jardy |first=Adam |url=https://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/sports/2015/08/27/0827-soccer-crew-sc-national-team-absences.html |title=Soccer {{!}} Crew: National teams could make 8 miss FC Dallas game|website=Dispatch.com|publisher=GateHouse Media|accessdate=3 August 2017|date=27 August 2015}}</ref> but returned to start every game in Crew SC's run to [[MLS Cup 2015]]. Against [[Portland Timbers]] in the final, he played the full 90 minutes and picked up a yellow card as Columbus was defeated 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2015-12-06-columbus-crew-sc-vs-portland-timbers/boxscore |title=Columbus Crew SC 1\u20132 Portland Timbers |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=6 December 2015}}</ref> Harrison made 14 appearances in his first season in Columbus and had his contract option picked up by the club on 7 December.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mlot |first=Josh |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2015/12/7/9868056/columbus-crew-sc-exercises-options-makes-cuts-as-2016-already-begins |title=Columbus Crew SC exercises options, makes cuts, as 2016 already begins to take shape |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHarrison was rumored to be leaving Columbus ahead of the [[2016 Columbus Crew SC season|2016 season]]. Reports from his native Ghana claimed that he would be joining [[Mersin \u0130dman Yurdu]] when his contract expired at the end of 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last=Guldan |first=Patrick |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2015/12/30/10690104/harrison-affuls-rumored-transfer-now-rumored-to-be-off |title=Harrison Afful's rumored transfer now rumored to be off |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=30 December 2015}}</ref> No transfer came to pass, however, and he returned to Columbus for his first full season with the Black and Gold. Although Harrison again missed time while appearing with Ghana, he did find the time to score his first MLS goal \u2014 a 54th-minute strike against [[Toronto FC]] on 13 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.columbuscrewsc.com/matchcenter/2016-07-13-columbus-crew-sc-vs-toronto-fc/boxscore |title=Columbus Crew SC 1\u20131 Toronto FC |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=13 July 2016}}</ref> He added two more goals in the final month of the season, scoring in a victory over [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] on 1 October,<ref>{{cite web |last=Clarkson |first=Nick |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2016/10/01/afful-meram-duka-provide-fireworks-final-home-match-2016 |title=Afful, Meram & Duka provide fireworks in final home match of 2016 |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=1 October 2016}}</ref> and a defeat against [[New York Red Bulls]] in the season finale on 16 October.<ref>{{cite web |last=Geigerman |first=Adam |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2016/10/16/crew-scs-comeback-falls-short-red-bull-arena |title=Crew SC's comeback falls short at Red Bull Arena |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=16 October 2016}}</ref> He did pick up a [[Penalty card#Red card|red card]] in a 1\u20131 draw with [[D.C. United]] on 16 July, but the card was rescinded by the league two days later.<ref>{{cite web |last=Blank |first=Dan |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/07/18/after-review-crew-sc-defender-harrison-afful-has-red-card-rescinded |title=After review, Crew SC defender Harrison Afful has red card rescinded |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=18 July 2016}}</ref> Harrison finished the season with three goals in 30 appearances and was ranked as the best right back in the league, according to the [[Audi]] Player Index.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Ghana-s-Harrison-Afful-named-best-right-back-in-MLS-479657 |title=Ghana\u2019s Harrison Afful named best right-back in MLS |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=22 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u20132019: Injuries and club struggles====\nHarrison's [[2017 Columbus Crew SC season|2017 season]] was marred by injuries \u2014 a knee laceration in March,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/sports/2017/March-6th/harrison-afful-picks-up-knee-injury.php |title=Harrison Afful picks up knee injury |website=MyJoyOnline.com |publisher=MGL Digital Media |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=6 March 2017}}</ref> a sliced nerve in his hand in April,<ref>{{cite web |last=Erickson |first=Andrew |url=https://www.dispatch.com/sports/20170411/crew-cuts-berhalter-swanson-diagnosed-with-severe-ankle-sprain |title=Crew Cuts: Berhalter: Swanson diagnosed with \u2018severe\u2019 ankle sprain |website=Dispatch.com |publisher=GateHouse Media |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=11 April 2017}}</ref> a thigh strain in late summer,<ref>{{cite web |last=Murphy |first=Pat |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2017/8/5/16102236/how-to-watch-columbus-crew-sc-vs-san-jose-earthquakes-mls-2017 |title=How to Watch: Columbus Crew SC vs. San Jose Earthquakes |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=5 August 2017 |quote=We do not expect...Harrison Afful (thigh strain) to feature in this one...}}</ref> and a sprained foot in October.<ref>{{cite web |last=Erickson |first=Andrew |url=https://www.dispatch.com/sports/20171004/crew-cuts-crew-sc-fighting-injury-bug-during-international-break |title=Crew Cuts: Crew SC fighting injury bug during international break |website=Dispatch.com |publisher=GateHouse Media |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=4 October 2017}}</ref> Although he did not score during the regular season, he saved his best for the [[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs]]. In the first leg of the conference semifinals against New York City FC, Harrison scored three minutes into stoppage time to give Columbus a 4\u20131 victory; that goal would end up being the difference as the club advanced by a 4\u20133 aggregate scoreline.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wahl |first=Grant |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/10/31/columbus-crew-nycfc-mls-playoffs-mapfre-stadium-callens-red-david-villa |title=Crew Pounce After Red Card, Put NYCFC in Corner in Playoff First Leg |website=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=31 October 2017}}</ref> He finished the season with one goal from 29 appearances and again had his contract option picked up by Crew SC.<ref>{{cite web |last=Murphy |first=Pat |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2017/12/1/16724820/columbus-crew-sc-exercise-options-on-nine-players-for-2018-mls |title=Columbus Crew SC exercise options on nine players for 2018 |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter a season of personal struggle in 2017, Harrison bounced back in [[2018 Columbus Crew SC season|2018]] with two goals and six assists in 35 appearances. In one three-game span in July and August, he provided an assist in each match and helped Columbus claim three consecutive victories.<ref>{{cite web |last=Scribner |first=Megan |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2018/08/10/recap-zardes-stoppage-time-game-winner-lifts-columbus-over-dynamo-1-0 |title=Zardes' stoppage-time game-winner lifts Columbus over Dynamo 1\u20130 |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> Harrison tallied the third-most shots on the team, behind only [[Gyasi Zardes]] and [[Pedro Miguel Martins Santos|Pedro Santos]]<ref>{{cite web |last=McCauley |first=Kim |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2018/10/27/18032270/columbus-crew-sc-minnesota-united-fc-2018-mls-decision-day-preview |title=At the end of a season full of distractions, the Columbus Crew just need a win |website=SBNation.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=27 October 2018}}</ref> but only tallied two goals: against [[San Jose Earthquakes]] in April and New York City FC in September.<ref name=MLSprofile>{{MLS|harrison-afful}}</ref> He added an assist in the knockout round of the [[2018 MLS Cup Playoffs]], helping Columbus to advance over D.C. United.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.columbuscrewsc.com/matchcenter/2018-11-01-dc-united-vs-columbus-crew-sc/boxscore |title=D.C. United 2 (2) \u2013 2 (3) Columbus Crew SC |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=1 November 2018}}</ref> Harrison also set a personal mark in a mid-season friendly against [[Deportivo Saprissa|Saprissa]]. He came on as a substitute and played as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] \u2014 the first time he had appeared for Columbus at any position other than right back.<ref>{{cite web |last=Scribner |first=Megan |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2018/07/03/recap-crew-sc-outlasts-rain-delay-defeats-deportivo-saprissa-2-0 |title=Crew SC outlasts rain delay, defeats Deportivo Saprissa 2\u20130 |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter an injury-free 2018, Harrison was limited to just 24 appearances in all competitions over the course of the [[2019 Columbus Crew SC season|2019 season]]. In a home match against [[Atlanta United FC|Atlanta United]] on 30 March, he collided with countryman [[Jonathan Mensah]] and suffered a [[Mandibular fracture|fractured jaw]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fisher|first=Tyler|url=https://www.massivereport.com/2019/4/2/18292272/columbus-crew-sc-harrison-afful-injury-broken-jaw-caleb-porter-hector-jimenez-mls-2019|title=Crew lose Afful for at least four to six weeks with a broken jaw|website=MassiveReport.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=2 April 2019}}</ref> Harrison would miss eleven matches due to the injury, returning on 11 June and making his [[U.S. Open Cup]] debut in a victory over [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Myers|first=Jacob|url=https://www.dispatch.com/sports/20190608/crew-sc--harrison-afful-could-return-to-lineup-for-open-cup-game|title=Harrison Afful could return to lineup for Open Cup game|website=Dispatch.com|publisher=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=8 June 2019}}</ref> Although he would not score on the year, Harrison provided two assists over a three-match span in August.<ref name=MLSprofile/> His contract expired following the season, but the Crew announced that the sides were still \"in negotiations\";<ref>{{cite web|author=Crew SC Communications|url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2019/10/21/columbus-crew-sc-announces-roster-updates-ahead-2020-season|title=Columbus Crew SC announces roster updates ahead of 2020 season|website=ColumbusCrewSC.com|publisher=[[Columbus Crew SC]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=21 October 2019}}</ref> nine days later, they agreed on a deal for Harrison to return to the club on a new contract.<ref>{{cite web|last=Guldan|first=Patrick|url=https://www.massivereport.com/2019/10/30/20939820/columbus-crew-sc-re-sign-harrison-afful-caleb-porter-mls-2019|title=Crew re-sign Harrison Afful|website=MassiveReport.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHarrison debuted in the Ghanaian international setup at the [[Ghana national under-20 football team|U20 level]],<ref name=AKSCinterview>{{cite web |last=Kyei Kumasi |first=David |url=http://www.asantekotokofc.org/Newreel/2008/000208/harrison_interview.htm |title=Exclusive Interview With Harrison Afful |website=AsanteKotokoFC.org |publisher=Asante Kotoko S.C. |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=23 February 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829060056/http://www.asantekotokofc.org/Newreel/2008/000208/harrison_interview.htm |archivedate=29 August 2009}}</ref> appearing six times and scoring a goal for the side. He struggled to lock down a place on the team outside 2006, however, and later said that \"my unsuccessful attempts at the junior national teams [were] not as a result of poor performance\".<ref name=AKSCinterview/>\n\n===Early career and AFCON tournaments===\n[[File:20150331 Mali vs Ghana 097.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Harrison has won three medals from [[Africa Cup of Nations]] tournaments.]]\nHarrison made his debut for the [[Ghana national football team|senior national team]] at the [[2008 Africa Cup of Nations]]. He had not been named in the preliminary 40-man squad<ref name=AKSCinterview/> but was called up to the final squad by coach [[Claude Le Roy]]. Harrison earned his first cap on 9 February in the third place match, entering as an 89th-minute substitute in the 4\u20132 victory over [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafonline50.com/?lng=1&module=resultats_national&rub=1&div=1&res=95849&ma=31&CmpetPere=0&cmpt=0 |title=Ghana 4\u20132 Ivory Coast |website=CAFOnline50.com |publisher=Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Africaine de Football |date=9 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214210815/http://www.cafonline50.com/?lng=1&module=resultats_national&rub=1&div=1&res=95849&ma=31&CmpetPere=0&cmpt=0 |archivedate=14 February 2008 |access-date=3 January 2017 }}</ref> Although Le Roy resigned in May 2008, Harrison continued to earn playing time under caretaker [[Sellas Tetteh]] and new manager [[Milovan Rajevac]]: he appeared 10 times in [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifying for the 2010 FIFA World Cup]], helping the Black Stars qualify for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|final tournament]] with games to spare.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/8240811.stm |title=Ghana qualify for 2010 World Cup |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=6 September 2009}}</ref> He was then called up to the [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations]], and although Ghana made a run to the [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations Final]] he did not make an appearance at the tournament. Harrison was left off Ghana's squad for the 2010 World Cup, failing to even crack the Black Stars' preliminary roster.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jordan |first=Andrew |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/398941-ghanas-2010-fifa-world-cup-squad-announced |title=2010 FIFA World Cup: Ghana's Squad Announced |website=[[Bleacher Report|BleacherReport.com]] |publisher=Turner Broadcasting System |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=30 May 2010}}</ref> After appearing against [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] in a friendly in August, Harrison would not earn another cap for nearly two years.<ref name=\"nft\">{{NFT player|id=24678}}</ref>\n\n===Buildup to and the 2014 World Cup===\nHarrison was finally recalled to the Black Stars in June 2012, as [[James Kwesi Appiah]] brought in the defender for a pair of [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Lesotho national football team|Lesotho]] and [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]].<ref name=\"nft\"/> After appearing just twice in qualifying for the tournament, Harrison was called up to the Ghanaian squad for the [[2013 Africa Cup of Nations]] alongside his club teammate [[Emmanuel Clottey]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Mensah |first=Kent |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4389/ghanaian-football/2013/01/09/3659849/asante-kotokos-rashid-sumaila-dropped-from-ghanas-final-23 |title=Asante Kotoko's Rashid Sumaila dropped from Ghana's final 23-man 2013 Afcon squad |website=Goal.com |publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=9 January 2013}}</ref> Harrison appeared five times at the tournament, missing only a group-stage draw against [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]]. He played 90 minutes in the third place playoff as the Black Stars were defeated 3\u20131 by [[Mali national football team|Mali]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Fottrell |first=Stephen |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/21387641 |title=2013 Africa Cup of Nations: Mali 3\u20131 Ghana |website=BBC.com |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=9 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 May 2014, Harrison was named in Ghana's 30-man preliminary squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]];<ref>{{cite web |last=Shardow |first=Ameenu |url=https://africanfootball.com/news/429196/Ghana-coach-submits-30-man-preliminary-squad-to-FIFA |title=Ghana coach submits 30-man preliminary squad to FIFA |website=AfricanFootball.com |publisher=African Football |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=16 May 2014}}</ref> he was then named to the final squad on 2 June.<ref>{{cite web |author=Telegraph Sport |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/ghana/10810459/Ghana-World-Cup-2014-squad.html |title=Ghana World Cup 2014 squad |website=Telegraph.co.uk |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=2 June 2014}}</ref> Harrison appeared twice as Ghana were eliminated in the group stage, providing an assist in a draw against eventual world champions [[Germany national football team|Germany]] on 21 June.<ref>{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/25285228 |title=World Cup: Germany 2\u20132 Ghana |website=BBC.com |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20150331 Mali vs Ghana 079.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Harrison captained Ghana for the first time at the age of 29.]]\n===AFCON success and World Cup qualifying failure===\nAfter appearing in all six matches in Ghana's [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] run, Harrison was named to the squad for the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|final tournament]] on 7 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanafa.org/pages/blackstars/201501/10013.php |title=Ghana names final squad for AFCON 2015 |website=GhanaFA.org |publisher=Ghana Football Association |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=7 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108161104/http://www.ghanafa.org/pages/blackstars/201501/10013.php |archivedate=8 January 2015 }}</ref> He appeared in every match at the tournament, helping the Black Stars reach the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations Final|final]] against Ivory Coast. As the eighth taker, Harrison scored his attempt in the penalty shootout, but Ghana were defeated 9\u20138 on spot kicks; for the second time, he finished as an AFCON runner-up.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chowdhury |first=Saj |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/30665978 |title=Afcon 2015 final as it happened |website=BBC.com |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=8 February 2015}}</ref> Later that year, Harrison captained Ghana for the first time, leading the team to a 3\u20132 victory over [[Congo national football team|Congo]] on 1 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/first-time-captain-harrison-afful-happy-to-lead-black-stars-to-win-over-congo |title=First-time captain Harrison Afful happy to lead Black Stars to win over Congo |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=25 September 2015 |date=2 September 2015}}</ref> He was back in an AFCON squad two years later, earning a place on the Ghanaian team for the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] on 4 January.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/afcon-2017-list-of-players-for-each-of-the-16-teams |title=Full squad lists of all 16 teams at the 2017 Africa Cup of Nations |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=9 January 2017}}</ref> Harrison played every minute in the tournament, helping the Black Stars to a fourth-place finish after falling to [[Burkina Faso national football team|Burkina Faso]] in the third place match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20170204-burkina-faso-snatches-third-place-africa-cup-nations-with-late-goal-ghana |title=Burkina Faso snatches third place in Africa Cup of Nations with late goal |website=France24.com |publisher=[[France24]] |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Ghana had appeared in three consecutive World Cups, the Black Stars failed in their bid to qualify for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]. Harrison appeared six times in [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifying]], including four matches in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CAF Third Round|third round]]<ref name=\"nft\"/> as Ghana placed third in their group and missed out on the World Cup for the first time since [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Reineking |first=Jim |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/worldcup/2018/06/11/world-cup-2018-notable-teams-failed-qualify-usmnt-italy/675930002/ |title=FIFA World Cup 2018: Notable teams that failed to qualify |website=[[USAToday.com]] |publisher=Gannett Company |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=11 June 2018}}</ref> In the fall of 2018, he returned to the Ghana team for the first time since the qualifying failure and made two appearances in [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group F|2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualifying]] as the Black Stars finalized a spot at the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Narkortu Teye |first=Prince |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-kenya-qualify-for-2019-africa-cup-of-nations-as-sierra/xp3so8k13vak15qd5pqanzf4w |title=Ghana & Kenya qualify for 2019 Africa Cup of Nations as Sierra Leone get kicked out from qualifiers |website=Goal.com |publisher=Goal |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|1 March 2020|<ref name=WFprofile/><ref name=\"sw\"/><ref name=MLSprofile/>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Cup<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearances in the [[U.S. Open Cup]]</ref>\n!colspan=2|Continental\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=8|[[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis|ES Tunis]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2009\u201310]]\n|[[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|CLP-1]]\n|18||2||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2013||18||2\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2010\u201311]]\n|CLP-1\n|17||0||0||0||10{{efn|Appearances in the [[CAF Champions League]]|name=CL}}||1||colspan=2|\u2013||27||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2011\u201312]]\n|CLP-1\n|16||0||0||0||11{{efn|name=CL}}||1||2{{efn|Appearances in the [[FIFA Club World Cup]]}}||0||29||1\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2012\u201313]]\n|CLP-1\n|17||3||0||0||11{{efn|name=CL}}||0||colspan=2|\u2013||28||3\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2013\u201314]]\n|CLP-1\n|27||4||0||0||10{{efn|name=CL}}||0||colspan=2|\u2013||37||4\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2014\u201315]]\n|CLP-1\n|23||2|||0||0||6{{efn|name=CL}}||2||colspan=2|\u2013||29||4\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2015\u201316]]\n|CLP-1\n|0||0||0||0||4{{efn|One appearance in the CAF Champions League, three appearances and one goal in the [[CAF Confederation Cup]]}}||1||colspan=2|\u2013||4||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!118!!11!!0!!0!!52!!5!!2!!0!!172!!16\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[Columbus Crew SC]]\n|[[2015 Columbus Crew SC season|2015]]\n|rowspan=6|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|9||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2013||5{{efn|Appearances in the [[MLS Cup Playoffs]]|name=MLS}}||0||14||0\n|-\n|[[2016 Columbus Crew SC season|2016]]\n|30||3||0||0||colspan=2|\u2013||colspan=2|\u2013||30||3\n|-\n|[[2017 Columbus Crew SC season|2017]]\n|24||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2013||5{{efn|name=MLS}}||1||29||1\n|-\n|[[2018 Columbus Crew SC season|2018]]\n|32||2||0||0||colspan=2|\u2013||3{{efn|name=MLS}}||0||35||2\n|-\n|[[2019 Columbus Crew SC season|2019]]\n|22||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2013||colspan=2|\u2013||24||0\n|-\n|[[2020 Columbus Crew SC season|2020]]\n|1||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2013||0||0||1||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!118!!5!!2!!0!!0!!0!!13!!1!!133!!6\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!236!!16!!2!!0!!52!!5!!15!!1!!305!!22\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n[[File:20150331 Mali vs Ghana 106.jpg|thumb|right|Harrison is one of the ten most-capped players in the history of the Ghanaian national team.]]\n{{updated|18 November 2018|<ref name=\"nft\"/>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=3|[[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2008||10||0\n|-\n|2009||7||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team 2010|2010]]||3||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team 2011|2011]]||0||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team 2012|2012]]||5||0\n|-\n|[[2013 Ghana national football team season|2013]]||14||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team results (2010\u201319)#2014|2014]]||10||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team results (2010\u201319)#2015|2015]]||14||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team results (2010\u201319)#2016|2016]]||8||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team results (2010\u201319)#2017|2017]]||11||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team results (2010\u201319)#2018|2018]]||2||0\n|-\n|[[Ghana national football team results (2010\u201319)#2019|2019]]||0||0\n|-\n!Total||84||0\n|}\n\n==Honors==\n===Club===\n'''Asante Kotoko'''\n* [[Ghana Premier League]]: 2008\n\n'''ES Tunis'''<ref name=TunisHonors/>\n* [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1]]: [[2009\u201310 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2009\u201310]], [[2010\u201311 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2010\u201311]], [[2011\u201312 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2011\u201312]], [[2013\u201314 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2013\u201314]]\n* [[Tunisian Cup]]: 2010\u201311\n* [[CAF Champions League]]: [[2011 CAF Champions League|2011]]\n\n===Individual===\n* [[Ghana Player of the Year|Ghanaian Footballer of the Year]]: 2015<ref>{{cite web |author=Editor |url=https://www.newsghana.com.gh/harrison-afful-crowned-swag-footballer-of-the-year/ |title=Harrison Afful crowned SWAG footballer of the year |website=NewsGhana.com.gh |publisher=News Ghana |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n* [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations#Awards|2015 Africa Cup of Nations Team of the Tournament]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafonline.com/en-US/NewsCenter/News/NewsDetails?id=N5LLNBRtUVsPZJSOkHVjrw%3D%3D |title=Orange AFCON 2015 awards and best XI |website=CAFOnline.com |publisher=Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Africaine de Football |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/players/harrison-afful Columbus profile]\n* {{MLS|harrison-afful}}\n* {{FIFA player|294626}}\n* {{Soccerway|harrison-afful/21414}}\n\n{{Columbus Crew SC squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Ghana squads\n|bg=#CA1118\n|fg=#FBE816\n|bordercolor=black\n|list1=\n{{Ghana squad 2008 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2010 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2013 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Ghana squad 2015 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2017 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{Ghanaian Footballer of the Year}}\n{{2015 Africa Cup of Nations Team of the Tournament}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Afful, Harrison}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Tema]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:West African Football Academy players]]\n[[Category:Asante Kotoko SC players]]\n[[Category:Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis players]]\n[[Category:Columbus Crew SC players]]\n[[Category:Ghana Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1 players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Ghana under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghana international footballers]]\n[[Category:2008 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2010 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2013 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2017 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Harrison Afful\n| image = 20150331 Mali vs Ghana 126.jpg\n| caption = Harrison with Ghana in 2015\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|7|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Tema]], [[Greater Accra Region|Greater Accra]], Ghana\n| height = 1.68 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Fullback]]\n| currentclub = [[Columbus Crew SC]]\n| clubnumber = 25\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]]\n| years1 = 2005\u20132009\n| clubs1 = [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]]\n| caps1 = 148\n| goals1 = 11\n| years2 = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Asante Kotoko S.C.|Asante Kotoko]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 68\n| goals2 = 5\n| years3 = 2009\u20132015\n| clubs3 = [[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis|ES Tunis]]\n| caps3 = 118\n| goals3 = 11\n| years4 = 2015\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Columbus Crew SC]]\n| caps4 = 118\n| goals4 = 5\n| nationalyears1 = 2006\n| nationalteam1 = [[Ghana national under-20 football team|Ghana U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2008\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 84\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Team|{{fb|Ghana}}}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]|[[2008 Africa Cup of Nations|2008]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]|[[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]|[[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]]}}\n| pcupdate = 1 March 2020\n| ntupdate = 18 November 2018\n}}\n\n'''Harrison Afful''' (born 24 July 1986), commonly [[Mononymous person|known simply as]] '''Harrison''', is a Ghanaian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|fullback]] for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Columbus Crew SC]] and the [[Ghana national football team|Ghanaian national team]]. He appeared previously for [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]] and [[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis|ES Tunis]] and spent time on loan to [[Asante Kotoko S.C.|Asante Kotoko]].\n\nHarrison came through the youth setup at the [[West African Football Academy|Feyenoord Academy]], spending his first two professional seasons on the Academy's senior team. He then moved on loan to Asante Kotoko, spending two seasons with the Porcupines and winning the [[Ghana Premier League]] in 2008. After four years of professional football, Harrison left Ghana for the first time to join ES Tunis of the [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1]]. He played the next six seasons with Tunis, appearing for the club more than 170 times. Tunis won four league titles during Harrison's time there, appeared in three [[CAF Champions League]] finals, and won the [[2011 CAF Champions League Final]]; Harrison scored the only goal over the two legs. In the summer of 2015, Harrison moved to the United States and signed for Columbus Crew SC, helping the club reach [[MLS Cup 2015]] in his first season.\n\nAt the international level, Harrison made his Ghanaian debut at the [[2008 Africa Cup of Nations]], helping Ghana to a third-place finish at that tournament. He has since appeared for the [[Ghana national football team|Black Stars]] at four more AFCON tournaments, finishing as runners-up in [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]] and [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]]. He was called up to Ghana's squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], appearing twice during the tournament. Harrison captained his nation for the first time in a [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly]] against [[Congo national football team|Congo]] on 1 September 2015.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Tema]], Harrison grew up {{convert|23|km|abbr=off}} away in [[Nungua]], Ghana. He used to watch the Ghana national team on television with his family before becoming a professional footballer.<ref name=Story>{{cite web |url=https://footballghana.com/even-if-i-get-one-minute-to-play-i-will-make-use-of-it-harrison-affuls-world-cup-story |title=\"Even if I get one minute to play, I will make use of it.\"- Harrison Afful's World Cup story |website=FootballGhana.com |publisher=Football Ghana |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Feyenoord Academy===\nHarrison joined the [[Feyenoord Ghana|Feyenoord Academy]] after being discovered as a youth by [[Sam Arday]] and went on to spend four years with the senior team.<ref>{{cite web |last=Abayateye |first=Michael |url=https://www.primenewsghana.com/sports/harrison-afful-s-tribute-to-sam-ardey.html |title=Harrison Afful\u2019s tribute to Sam Arday |website=PrimeNewsGhana.com |publisher=Prime Network Ltd. |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=13 February 2017}}</ref> Although he spent two of those seasons on loan to [[Asante Kotoko S.C.]], Harrison appeared 148 times in total and scored 11 goals for the Academy. In 2008, he went on a trial with the Academy's parent club, [[Feyenoord]]. He was linked with a move to [[F.C. Copenhagen|K\u00f8benhavn]] but was told that he was too small and returned to Ghana.<ref name=Story/> He also spent time training with [[Helsingborgs IF|Helsingborgs]] in December of that year but failed to land a deal after suffering a [[hamstring injury]] while he was in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/content/view/2222/51/ |title=Afful fails to land Sweden deal |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |date=11 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818234752/http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/content/view/2222/51/ |archivedate=18 August 2009 |access-date=27 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Asante Kotoko====\nHarrison joined Asante Kotoko on loan at the start of the 2007 season, the first time he had played at a club other than the Feyenoord Academy. The loan move was made possible through a clause in [[Jordan Opoku]]'s contract. He had been bought by Asante Kotoko the year before, and his contract allowed Kotoko to choose one player to bring in on loan from the Academy. They exercised it by choosing Harrison.<ref name=Osmaninterview>{{cite web |last=Osman |first=Rahman |url=http://sport.citifmonline.com/2015/07/07/harrison-afful-small-man-huge-drive-and-passion/ |title=Harrison Afful: Small man, huge drive and passion |website=CitiFMOnline.com |publisher=Citi Newsroom |accessdate=20 December 2018 |date=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nKotoko head coach Bashiru Hayford handed Harrison his debut with a 10-minute cameo in a friendly match. This allowed the defender to break into the first team after initially appearing to be outside Hayford's plans.<ref name=Osmaninterview/> Harrison went on to spend two seasons on loan to Kotoko. He scored five goals in 68 appearances during his time at the club, winning the [[Ghana Premier League]] in 2008, and was named the league's Player of the Year that season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.remingtonellis.com/players/harrisonafful/ |title=Harrison Afful at Remington Ellis Management |website=RemingtonEllis.com |publisher=Remington Ellis Management Group |accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref> He also made his national team debut while at Kotoko.<ref name=Story/>\n\n===ES Tunis===\n====2009\u20132010: Early career in Tunisia====\nOn 25 August 2009, Harrison officially signed a three-year contract with [[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis]] (EST). He had trained with the club prior to the announcement and had scored a goal in a friendly match, helping convince Tunis to complete the signing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/10609/esperance-sign-afful.php |title=Esperance sign Afful |website=Kickoff.com |publisher=[[Kick Off (magazine)|KICK OFF magazine]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=25 August 2009}}</ref> The move to the [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1]] side marked the first time Harrison had signed for a club outside Ghana. He made his debut for EST on 12 September, playing the full 90 minutes in a 4\u20130 victory over [[CS Sfaxien]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/report/ligue-1-2009-2010-esperance-tunis-club-sportif-sfaxien/ |title=ES Tunis 4\u20130 CS Sfaxien |website=WorldFootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL Medien GmbH & Co. KG |accessdate=21 December 2018 |date=12 September 2009}}</ref> Harrison scored his first two goals for the club in a three-round span in the spring of 2010, tallying against [[CA Bizertin]] on 28 April and [[ES Hammam-Sousse]] on 15 May.<ref name=WFprofile>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/harrison-afful/2/ |title=Harrison Afful at WorldFootball.net |website=WorldFootball.net |publisher=HEIM:SPIEL Medien GmbH & Co. KG |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> He finished the season with two goals from 18 appearances as Tunis claimed their second consecutive CLP-1 title.<ref name=TunisHonors>{{cite web |url=http://www.est.org.tn/palmares-foot.php |title=ES Tunis \u2013 Palmar\u00e8s Football |website=EST.org.tn |publisher=Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis |accessdate=19 December 2018 |language=French |trans-title=ES Tunis \u2013 Football Honors}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u20132013: Champions League success====\nIn his [[2010\u201311 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|second season]] at ES Tunis, Harrison did not play a large role in league play. He appeared 17 times without a goal as the Blood and Gold claimed their third consecutive league title.<ref name=TunisHonors/> Instead, he became a fixture in the Tunis squad in [[2010 CAF Champions League|CAF Champions League]] play. Harrison made his debut in the tournament on 16 July 2010, appearing in Group A play against [[ES S\u00e9tif]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2010/07/16/africa/caf-champions-league/entente-sportive-de-setif/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/935532/ |title=ES S\u00e9tif 0\u20131 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=16 July 2010}}</ref> He went on to appear in every game of the tournament from the group stage on, helping lead EST to the [[2010 CAF Champions League Final]]. Against [[TP Mazembe]] in the final, Harrison played 90 minutes in the first leg in a 5\u20130 defeat for Tunis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafonline.com/competition/champions-league_2010/news/6994-mazembe-move-within-touching-distance.html |title=Mazembe move within touching distance |website=CAFOnline.com |publisher=[[Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Africaine de Football]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=31 October 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918022832/http://www.cafonline.com/competition/champions-league_2010/news/6994-mazembe-move-within-touching-distance.html |archivedate=18 September 2012}}</ref> He scored in the 24th minute of the second leg, his first-ever goal in the competition, but Tunis could only manage a 1\u20131 draw and were defeated on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/9187255.stm |title=TP Mazembe claim African Champions League crown again |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=13 November 2010}}</ref> On the season, Harrison appeared 27 times in all competitions and scored once.\n\n[[File:Harrison Afful.jpg|thumb|230px|right|Harrison scored twice in five [[CAF Champions League]] Final appearances with Tunis.]]\nJust as in the prior season, Harrison played sparingly in the CLP-1, failing to make a league appearance until ES Tunis had concluded their Champions League run. He appeared in 16 league matches without scoring as Tunis rolled to a fourth consecutive league crown.<ref name=TunisHonors/> In [[2011 CAF Champions League|CAF Champions League]] play, Harrison again played a headlining role once the group stage began as Tunis eliminated [[Al-Hilal Club (Omdurman)|Al-Hilal]] in the semifinals and advanced to the continental final for the second consecutive year. He came off the bench in the first leg of the [[2011 CAF Champions League Final]], replacing [[Wajdi Bouazzi]] in the 90th minute of a draw with [[Wydad AC|Wydad Casablanca]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2011/11/06/africa/caf-champions-league/wydad-athletic-club/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1219381/ |title=Wydad Casablanca 0\u20130 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=6 November 2011}}</ref> Harrison started in the second leg, playing at right back at the [[Stade 7 November]]. In the 22nd minute, he placed a left-footed, curling shot into the upper corner, a goal that gave Tunis a 1\u20130 lead on the night and eventually the second Champions League title in club history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/15708355 |title=Esperance crowned African champions with win over Wydad |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=12 November 2011}}</ref> Harrison would later rate that goal as his favorite soccer memory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/players/harrison-afful |title=Harrison Afful \u2013 Columbus Crew SC profile |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=[[Columbus Crew SC]] |accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> By virtue of winning the Champions League, Tunis qualified for the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup]]; Harrison appeared off the bench in the quarterfinals against [[Al Sadd SC|Al Sadd]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=257429/match=300180904/report.html |title=ES Tunis 1\u20132 Al Sadd |website=FIFA.com |publisher=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=11 December 2011}}</ref> and started the fifth place match against [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=257441/match=300180903/report.html |title=Monterrey 3\u20132 ES Tunis |website=FIFA.com |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=10 August 2017 |date=14 December 2011}}</ref> On the season, he played 29 times in all competitions, scoring once.\n\nAlthough Harrison's contract with ES Tunis expired at the end of June, he re-signed with the club on 2 July 2012, inking a three-year contract extension that ran through the end of June 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/harrison-afful-signs-new-esperance-deal-2 |title=Harrison Afful signs new Esperance deal |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=2 July 2012}}</ref> With his contract situation resolved, he found his scoring boots in CLP-1 play, scoring goals against [[ES Zarzis]] on 21 November,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/11/21/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/esperance-sportive-de-zarzis/1403708/ |title=ES Tunis 2\u20131 ES Zarzis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=21 November 2012}}</ref> [[JS Kairouan]] on 8 December,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/12/08/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/js-kairouanaise/1403721/ |title=ES Tunis 5\u20131 JS Kairouan |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=8 December 2012}}</ref> and [[Club Africain]] on 31 March<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/03/31/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/club-africain/1465991/ |title=ES Tunis 3\u20131 Club Africain |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=31 March 2013}}</ref> \u2014 all matches that ended in victories for Tunis. Harrison again played a vital role for EST in the [[2012 CAF Champions League|Champions League]]. He helped the Blood and Gold eliminate Mazembe in the semifinals and advance to their third consecutive final to take on [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]]. He played 73 minutes in the first leg of the [[2012 CAF Champions League Final]], helping Tunis earn a 1\u20131 draw<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/11/04/africa/caf-champions-league/al-ahly/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1284936/ |title=Al Ahly 1\u20131 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=4 November 2012}}</ref> but was suspended for the second leg due to [[Penalty card#Yellow card|yellow card]] accumulation<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Afful-suspended-for-Champions-League-final-255407?channel=D1 |title=Afful suspended for Champions League final |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=GhanaWeb |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=5 November 2012}}</ref> as Tunis were defeated by a 3\u20132 aggregate scoreline.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/harrison-afful-and-esperance-miss-out-on-caf-champions-league-trophy?replytocom=176631 |title=Harrison Afful and Esperance miss out on CAF Champions League trophy |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=11 August 2017 |date=17 November 2012}}</ref> Harrison appeared 28 times in all competitions on the campaign, scoring three goals.\n\n====2013\u20132015: Final seasons at EST====\n[[2013\u201314 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2013\u201314]] would turn out to be the busiest and most prolific season of Harrison's career to date. He appeared in a career-high 37 matches in all competitions and scored four goals. In CLP-1 play, he scored twice before the turn of the year, tallying against [[Stade Tunisien]] on 3 November<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/11/03/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/stade-tunisien/1551406/ |title=ES Tunis 5\u20130 Stade Tunisien |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=3 November 2013}}</ref> and [[LPS Tozeur]] on 25 December.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/12/25/tunisia/ligue-1/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/lp-tozeur-avenir/1551456/ |title=ES Tunis 4\u20130 LPS Tozeur |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=25 December 2013}}</ref> He continued his form after new head coach [[Ruud Krol]] was hired, scoring in the return fixture against Tunisien on 15 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/02/15/tunisia/ligue-1/stade-tunisien/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1644989/ |title=Stade Tunisien 0\u20132 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=15 February 2014}}</ref> He tallyed the game-winning goal against Sfaxien on 2 April<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/04/02/tunisia/ligue-1/club-sportif-sfaxien/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/1645020/ |title=CS Sfaxien 0\u20131 ES Tunis |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=2 April 2014}}</ref> as Tunis claimed their fourth league title in Harrison's five seasons at the club.<ref name=TunisHonors/> He added ten more appearances in the [[2013 CAF Champions League|Champions League]], but EST were defeated by [[Orlando Pirates F.C.|Orlando Pirates]] in the semifinals and denied a fourth consecutive trip to the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/10/19/africa/caf-champions-league/esperance-sportive-de-tunis/orlando-pirates/1473572/ |title=Orlando Pirates 1\u20131 ES Tunis (1\u20131 agg.) |website=Soccerway.com |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Harrison was the subject of transfer interest, with reports from his native Ghana claiming that he was the subject of an offer from [[Olympique de Marseille]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Marseille-make-offer-to-sign-Harrison-Afful-306438 |title=Marseille make offer to sign Harrison Afful |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=GhanaWeb |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=16 April 2014}}</ref> The [[Ligue 1]] club were reportedly looking to sign Harrison before the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] began, in an effort to keep down the player's price. Following the domestic season, however, ES Tunis announced that Harrison would not leave the club until after the World Cup at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web |last=Talaat |first=Tarek |url=https://www.supersport.com/football/africa/news/140501/Harrison_Afful_to_stay_at_Esperance |title=Harrison Afful to stay at Esperance |website=[[SuperSport.com]] |publisher=MultiChoice Ltd. |accessdate=12 August 2017 |date=1 May 2014}}</ref> He continued to attract interest after the World Cup, with a reported 13 European clubs battling for his signature;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-defender-harrison-afful-attracts-13-offers-europe-excellent-world-cup?comment=1 |title=Ghana defender Harrison Afful attracts 13 offers from Europe after excellent World Cup |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=11 July 2014}}</ref> however, it was [[Al Wahda FC|Al Wahda]], of the United Arab Emirates, who had reportedly won the race for the defender. Harrison underwent a medical with the Clarets, but the club canceled the deal after ES Tunis broke off communication and he thus returned to Tunisia.<ref>{{cite web |last=Passela |first=Amith |url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/al-wahda-break-off-deal-for-ghana-s-harrison-afful-1.2849?videoId=5612976228001 |title=Al Wahda break off deal for Ghana\u2019s Harrison Afful |website=TheNational.ae |publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter any potential move in the summer fell through, Harrison returned to Tunis to begin the [[2014\u201315 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2014\u201315 season]]. On 31 August, in a match away to Bizertin, he scored two goals to help EST claim a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanastar.com/sports/ghanaian-defender-harrison-afful-hits-brace-for-esperance-de-tunis/ |title=Ghanaian Defender Harrison Afful Hits Brace for Esperance de Tunis |website=GhanaStar.com |publisher=Ghana Star |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=1 September 2014}}</ref> Harrison would not score again for the remainder of the league's season as Esp\u00e9rance placed third in the CLP-1, their lowest league finish during Harrison's time at the club. In [[2014 CAF Champions League]] play, he scored in both the first and second qualifying rounds, helping Tunis advance over [[Gor Mahia F.C.|Gor Mahia]] and [[AS Real Bamako|Real Bamako]], respectively.<ref name=\"sw\">{{Soccerway|harrison-afful/21414}}</ref> EST were eliminated in the group stage, however, the first time they had failed to advance to the knockout rounds since Harrison had joined the club. He finished the season with 29 appearances in all competitions, scoring four goals.\n\nWith his contract set to expire at the end of June, Harrison was rumored to be re-signing a two-year deal with the Blood and Gold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/soccer_transfers/Harrison-Afful-to-extend-Esperance-contract-359987?channel=D1 |title=Harrison Afful to extend Esperance contract |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=28 May 2015}}</ref> In the final month of his contract, he appeared four times and scored a goal for Tunis in continental competitions. However, Harrison and the club could not agree on a contract, and he departed after more than six seasons with Tunis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Afful-leaves-Esperance-after-six-seasons-366062 |title=Afful leaves Esperance after six seasons |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=2 July 2015}}</ref> Harrison appeared 172 times and scored 16 goals for Esperance.\n\n====FIFA case====\nFollowing his departure from Tunis at the end of June 2015, Harrison was reportedly not paid the remaining salaries and bonuses owed to him by the club. He filed a case with [[FIFA]] over the issue, and in May 2016 the organization sided with Harrison in the case. FIFA ordered Esp\u00e9rance to pay the remaining monies within one month of the ruling date; if they failed to do so, they would be docked six points in league play. FIFA also ruled that if the debts persisted, Tunis would be relegated to the [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 2]]. The club also paid a fine \"in the tens of thousands of Swiss francs to FIFA\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/FIFA-orders-Esperance-to-pay-Harrison-Afful-442587 |title=FIFA orders Esperance to pay Harrison Afful |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=22 December 2018 |date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Columbus Crew SC===\n====2015\u20132016: Initial years in Columbus====\nAfter his contract with Tunis expired at the end of June, Harrison joined [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Columbus Crew SC]] as a Discovery Signing.<ref>{{cite web |author=Crew SC Communications |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2015/07/30/crew-sc-signs-defender-harrison-afful |title=Crew SC signs defender Harrison Afful |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=30 July 2015}}</ref> Although the transfer was announced on 30 July 2015, he was only added to the roster after securing his visa and thus had to wait to make his club debut until 19 August. He started a 2\u20132 draw with [[New York City FC]], playing 60 minutes before being replaced by [[Hector Jim\u00e9nez (soccer)|Hector Jim\u00e9nez]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2015-08-19-columbus-crew-sc-vs-new-york-city-fc/boxscore |title=Columbus Crew SC 2\u20132 New York City FC |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=19 August 2015}}</ref> Harrison missed several matches while on international duty<ref>{{cite web |last=Jardy |first=Adam |url=https://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/sports/2015/08/27/0827-soccer-crew-sc-national-team-absences.html |title=Soccer {{!}} Crew: National teams could make 8 miss FC Dallas game|website=Dispatch.com|publisher=GateHouse Media|accessdate=3 August 2017|date=27 August 2015}}</ref> but returned to start every game in Crew SC's run to [[MLS Cup 2015]]. Against [[Portland Timbers]] in the final, he played the full 90 minutes and picked up a yellow card as Columbus was defeated 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2015-12-06-columbus-crew-sc-vs-portland-timbers/boxscore |title=Columbus Crew SC 1\u20132 Portland Timbers |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=6 December 2015}}</ref> Harrison made 14 appearances in his first season in Columbus and had his contract option picked up by the club on 7 December.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mlot |first=Josh |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2015/12/7/9868056/columbus-crew-sc-exercises-options-makes-cuts-as-2016-already-begins |title=Columbus Crew SC exercises options, makes cuts, as 2016 already begins to take shape |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=3 August 2017 |date=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHarrison was rumored to be leaving Columbus ahead of the [[2016 Columbus Crew SC season|2016 season]]. Reports from his native Ghana claimed that he would be joining [[Mersin \u0130dman Yurdu]] when his contract expired at the end of 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last=Guldan |first=Patrick |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2015/12/30/10690104/harrison-affuls-rumored-transfer-now-rumored-to-be-off |title=Harrison Afful's rumored transfer now rumored to be off |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=30 December 2015}}</ref> No transfer came to pass, however, and he returned to Columbus for his first full season with the Black and Gold. Although Harrison again missed time while appearing with Ghana, he did find the time to score his first MLS goal \u2014 a 54th-minute strike against [[Toronto FC]] on 13 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.columbuscrewsc.com/matchcenter/2016-07-13-columbus-crew-sc-vs-toronto-fc/boxscore |title=Columbus Crew SC 1\u20131 Toronto FC |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=13 July 2016}}</ref> He added two more goals in the final month of the season, scoring in a victory over [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] on 1 October,<ref>{{cite web |last=Clarkson |first=Nick |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2016/10/01/afful-meram-duka-provide-fireworks-final-home-match-2016 |title=Afful, Meram & Duka provide fireworks in final home match of 2016 |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=1 October 2016}}</ref> and a defeat against [[New York Red Bulls]] in the season finale on 16 October.<ref>{{cite web |last=Geigerman |first=Adam |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2016/10/16/crew-scs-comeback-falls-short-red-bull-arena |title=Crew SC's comeback falls short at Red Bull Arena |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=16 October 2016}}</ref> He did pick up a [[Penalty card#Red card|red card]] in a 1\u20131 draw with [[D.C. United]] on 16 July, but the card was rescinded by the league two days later.<ref>{{cite web |last=Blank |first=Dan |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/07/18/after-review-crew-sc-defender-harrison-afful-has-red-card-rescinded |title=After review, Crew SC defender Harrison Afful has red card rescinded |website=MLSSoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=4 August 2017 |date=18 July 2016}}</ref> Harrison finished the season with three goals in 30 appearances and was ranked as the best right back in the league, according to the [[Audi]] Player Index.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Ghana-s-Harrison-Afful-named-best-right-back-in-MLS-479657 |title=Ghana\u2019s Harrison Afful named best right-back in MLS |website=GhanaWeb.com |publisher=Ghana Web |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=22 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u20132019: Injuries and club struggles====\nHarrison's [[2017 Columbus Crew SC season|2017 season]] was marred by injuries \u2014 a knee laceration in March,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/sports/2017/March-6th/harrison-afful-picks-up-knee-injury.php |title=Harrison Afful picks up knee injury |website=MyJoyOnline.com |publisher=MGL Digital Media |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=6 March 2017}}</ref> a sliced nerve in his hand in April,<ref>{{cite web |last=Erickson |first=Andrew |url=https://www.dispatch.com/sports/20170411/crew-cuts-berhalter-swanson-diagnosed-with-severe-ankle-sprain |title=Crew Cuts: Berhalter: Swanson diagnosed with \u2018severe\u2019 ankle sprain |website=Dispatch.com |publisher=GateHouse Media |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=11 April 2017}}</ref> a thigh strain in late summer,<ref>{{cite web |last=Murphy |first=Pat |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2017/8/5/16102236/how-to-watch-columbus-crew-sc-vs-san-jose-earthquakes-mls-2017 |title=How to Watch: Columbus Crew SC vs. San Jose Earthquakes |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=5 August 2017 |quote=We do not expect...Harrison Afful (thigh strain) to feature in this one...}}</ref> and a sprained foot in October.<ref>{{cite web |last=Erickson |first=Andrew |url=https://www.dispatch.com/sports/20171004/crew-cuts-crew-sc-fighting-injury-bug-during-international-break |title=Crew Cuts: Crew SC fighting injury bug during international break |website=Dispatch.com |publisher=GateHouse Media |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=4 October 2017}}</ref> Although he did not score during the regular season, he saved his best for the [[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs]]. In the first leg of the conference semifinals against New York City FC, Harrison scored three minutes into stoppage time to give Columbus a 4\u20131 victory; that goal would end up being the difference as the club advanced by a 4\u20133 aggregate scoreline.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wahl |first=Grant |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/10/31/columbus-crew-nycfc-mls-playoffs-mapfre-stadium-callens-red-david-villa |title=Crew Pounce After Red Card, Put NYCFC in Corner in Playoff First Leg |website=SI.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=31 October 2017}}</ref> He finished the season with one goal from 29 appearances and again had his contract option picked up by Crew SC.<ref>{{cite web |last=Murphy |first=Pat |url=https://www.massivereport.com/2017/12/1/16724820/columbus-crew-sc-exercise-options-on-nine-players-for-2018-mls |title=Columbus Crew SC exercise options on nine players for 2018 |website=MassiveReport.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter a season of personal struggle in 2017, Harrison bounced back in [[2018 Columbus Crew SC season|2018]] with two goals and six assists in 35 appearances. In one three-game span in July and August, he provided an assist in each match and helped Columbus claim three consecutive victories.<ref>{{cite web |last=Scribner |first=Megan |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2018/08/10/recap-zardes-stoppage-time-game-winner-lifts-columbus-over-dynamo-1-0 |title=Zardes' stoppage-time game-winner lifts Columbus over Dynamo 1\u20130 |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=10 August 2018}}</ref> Harrison tallied the third-most shots on the team, behind only [[Gyasi Zardes]] and [[Pedro Miguel Martins Santos|Pedro Santos]]<ref>{{cite web |last=McCauley |first=Kim |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2018/10/27/18032270/columbus-crew-sc-minnesota-united-fc-2018-mls-decision-day-preview |title=At the end of a season full of distractions, the Columbus Crew just need a win |website=SBNation.com |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=27 October 2018}}</ref> but only tallied two goals: against [[San Jose Earthquakes]] in April and New York City FC in September.<ref name=MLSprofile>{{MLS|harrison-afful}}</ref> He added an assist in the knockout round of the [[2018 MLS Cup Playoffs]], helping Columbus to advance over D.C. United.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://matchcenter.columbuscrewsc.com/matchcenter/2018-11-01-dc-united-vs-columbus-crew-sc/boxscore |title=D.C. United 2 (2) \u2013 2 (3) Columbus Crew SC |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=1 November 2018}}</ref> Harrison also set a personal mark in a mid-season friendly against [[Deportivo Saprissa|Saprissa]]. He came on as a substitute and played as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] \u2014 the first time he had appeared for Columbus at any position other than right back.<ref>{{cite web |last=Scribner |first=Megan |url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2018/07/03/recap-crew-sc-outlasts-rain-delay-defeats-deportivo-saprissa-2-0 |title=Crew SC outlasts rain delay, defeats Deportivo Saprissa 2\u20130 |website=ColumbusCrewSC.com |publisher=Columbus Crew SC |accessdate=19 December 2018 |date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter an injury-free 2018, Harrison was limited to just 24 appearances in all competitions over the course of the [[2019 Columbus Crew SC season|2019 season]]. In a home match against [[Atlanta United FC|Atlanta United]] on 30 March, he collided with countryman [[Jonathan Mensah]] and suffered a [[Mandibular fracture|fractured jaw]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fisher|first=Tyler|url=https://www.massivereport.com/2019/4/2/18292272/columbus-crew-sc-harrison-afful-injury-broken-jaw-caleb-porter-hector-jimenez-mls-2019|title=Crew lose Afful for at least four to six weeks with a broken jaw|website=MassiveReport.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=2 April 2019}}</ref> Harrison would miss eleven matches due to the injury, returning on 11 June and making his [[U.S. Open Cup]] debut in a victory over [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Myers|first=Jacob|url=https://www.dispatch.com/sports/20190608/crew-sc--harrison-afful-could-return-to-lineup-for-open-cup-game|title=Harrison Afful could return to lineup for Open Cup game|website=Dispatch.com|publisher=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=8 June 2019}}</ref> Although he would not score on the year, Harrison provided two assists over a three-match span in August.<ref name=MLSprofile/> His contract expired following the season, but the Crew announced that the sides were still \"in negotiations\";<ref>{{cite web|author=Crew SC Communications|url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2019/10/21/columbus-crew-sc-announces-roster-updates-ahead-2020-season|title=Columbus Crew SC announces roster updates ahead of 2020 season|website=ColumbusCrewSC.com|publisher=[[Columbus Crew SC]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=21 October 2019}}</ref> nine days later, they agreed on a deal for Harrison to return to the club on a new contract.<ref>{{cite web|last=Guldan|first=Patrick|url=https://www.massivereport.com/2019/10/30/20939820/columbus-crew-sc-re-sign-harrison-afful-caleb-porter-mls-2019|title=Crew re-sign Harrison Afful|website=MassiveReport.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHarrison debuted in the Ghanaian international setup at the [[Ghana national under-20 football team|U20 level]],<ref name=AKSCinterview>{{cite web |last=Kyei Kumasi |first=David |url=http://www.asantekotokofc.org/Newreel/2008/000208/harrison_interview.htm |title=Exclusive Interview With Harrison Afful |website=AsanteKotokoFC.org |publisher=Asante Kotoko S.C. |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=23 February 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829060056/http://www.asantekotokofc.org/Newreel/2008/000208/harrison_interview.htm |archivedate=29 August 2009}}</ref> appearing six times and scoring a goal for the side. He struggled to lock down a place on the team outside 2006, however, and later said that \"my unsuccessful attempts at the junior national teams [were] not as a result of poor performance\".<ref name=AKSCinterview/>\n\n===Early career and AFCON tournaments===\n[[File:20150331 Mali vs Ghana 097.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Harrison has won three medals from [[Africa Cup of Nations]] tournaments.]]\nHarrison made his debut for the [[Ghana national football team|senior national team]] at the [[2008 Africa Cup of Nations]]. He had not been named in the preliminary 40-man squad<ref name=AKSCinterview/> but was called up to the final squad by coach [[Claude Le Roy]]. Harrison earned his first cap on 9 February in the third place match, entering as an 89th-minute substitute in the 4\u20132 victory over [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafonline50.com/?lng=1&module=resultats_national&rub=1&div=1&res=95849&ma=31&CmpetPere=0&cmpt=0 |title=Ghana 4\u20132 Ivory Coast |website=CAFOnline50.com |publisher=Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Africaine de Football |date=9 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214210815/http://www.cafonline50.com/?lng=1&module=resultats_national&rub=1&div=1&res=95849&ma=31&CmpetPere=0&cmpt=0 |archivedate=14 February 2008 |access-date=3 January 2017 }}</ref> Although Le Roy resigned in May 2008, Harrison continued to earn playing time under caretaker [[Sellas Tetteh]] and new manager [[Milovan Rajevac]]: he appeared 10 times in [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifying for the 2010 FIFA World Cup]], helping the Black Stars qualify for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|final tournament]] with games to spare.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/8240811.stm |title=Ghana qualify for 2010 World Cup |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=6 September 2009}}</ref> He was then called up to the [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations]], and although Ghana made a run to the [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations Final]] he did not make an appearance at the tournament. Harrison was left off Ghana's squad for the 2010 World Cup, failing to even crack the Black Stars' preliminary roster.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jordan |first=Andrew |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/398941-ghanas-2010-fifa-world-cup-squad-announced |title=2010 FIFA World Cup: Ghana's Squad Announced |website=[[Bleacher Report|BleacherReport.com]] |publisher=Turner Broadcasting System |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=30 May 2010}}</ref> After appearing against [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] in a friendly in August, Harrison would not earn another cap for nearly two years.<ref name=\"nft\">{{NFT player|id=24678}}</ref>\n\n===Buildup to and the 2014 World Cup===\nHarrison was finally recalled to the Black Stars in June 2012, as [[James Kwesi Appiah]] brought in the defender for a pair of [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Lesotho national football team|Lesotho]] and [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]].<ref name=\"nft\"/> After appearing just twice in qualifying for the tournament, Harrison was called up to the Ghanaian squad for the [[2013 Africa Cup of Nations]] alongside his club teammate [[Emmanuel Clottey]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Mensah |first=Kent |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4389/ghanaian-football/2013/01/09/3659849/asante-kotokos-rashid-sumaila-dropped-from-ghanas-final-23 |title=Asante Kotoko's Rashid Sumaila dropped from Ghana's final 23-man 2013 Afcon squad |website=Goal.com |publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=9 January 2013}}</ref> Harrison appeared five times at the tournament, missing only a group-stage draw against [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]]. He played 90 minutes in the third place playoff as the Black Stars were defeated 3\u20131 by [[Mali national football team|Mali]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Fottrell |first=Stephen |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/21387641 |title=2013 Africa Cup of Nations: Mali 3\u20131 Ghana |website=BBC.com |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=9 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 May 2014, Harrison was named in Ghana's 30-man preliminary squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]];<ref>{{cite web |last=Shardow |first=Ameenu |url=https://africanfootball.com/news/429196/Ghana-coach-submits-30-man-preliminary-squad-to-FIFA |title=Ghana coach submits 30-man preliminary squad to FIFA |website=AfricanFootball.com |publisher=African Football |accessdate=25 December 2018 |date=16 May 2014}}</ref> he was then named to the final squad on 2 June.<ref>{{cite web |author=Telegraph Sport |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/ghana/10810459/Ghana-World-Cup-2014-squad.html |title=Ghana World Cup 2014 squad |website=Telegraph.co.uk |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=2 June 2014}}</ref> Harrison appeared twice as Ghana were eliminated in the group stage, providing an assist in a draw against eventual world champions [[Germany national football team|Germany]] on 21 June.<ref>{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/25285228 |title=World Cup: Germany 2\u20132 Ghana |website=BBC.com |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20150331 Mali vs Ghana 079.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Harrison captained Ghana for the first time at the age of 29.]]\n===AFCON success and World Cup qualifying failure===\nAfter appearing in all six matches in Ghana's [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] run, Harrison was named to the squad for the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|final tournament]] on 7 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanafa.org/pages/blackstars/201501/10013.php |title=Ghana names final squad for AFCON 2015 |website=GhanaFA.org |publisher=Ghana Football Association |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=7 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108161104/http://www.ghanafa.org/pages/blackstars/201501/10013.php |archivedate=8 January 2015 }}</ref> He appeared in every match at the tournament, helping the Black Stars reach the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations Final|final]] against Ivory Coast. As the eighth taker, Harrison scored his attempt in the penalty shootout, but Ghana were defeated 9\u20138 on spot kicks; for the second time, he finished as an AFCON runner-up.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chowdhury |first=Saj |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/30665978 |title=Afcon 2015 final as it happened |website=BBC.com |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=8 February 2015}}</ref> Later that year, Harrison captained Ghana for the first time, leading the team to a 3\u20132 victory over [[Congo national football team|Congo]] on 1 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/first-time-captain-harrison-afful-happy-to-lead-black-stars-to-win-over-congo |title=First-time captain Harrison Afful happy to lead Black Stars to win over Congo |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=25 September 2015 |date=2 September 2015}}</ref> He was back in an AFCON squad two years later, earning a place on the Ghanaian team for the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] on 4 January.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/afcon-2017-list-of-players-for-each-of-the-16-teams |title=Full squad lists of all 16 teams at the 2017 Africa Cup of Nations |website=GhanaSoccernet.com |publisher=Ghana Soccernet |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=9 January 2017}}</ref> Harrison played every minute in the tournament, helping the Black Stars to a fourth-place finish after falling to [[Burkina Faso national football team|Burkina Faso]] in the third place match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.france24.com/en/20170204-burkina-faso-snatches-third-place-africa-cup-nations-with-late-goal-ghana |title=Burkina Faso snatches third place in Africa Cup of Nations with late goal |website=France24.com |publisher=[[France24]] |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Ghana had appeared in three consecutive World Cups, the Black Stars failed in their bid to qualify for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]. Harrison appeared six times in [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifying]], including four matches in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CAF Third Round|third round]]<ref name=\"nft\"/> as Ghana placed third in their group and missed out on the World Cup for the first time since [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Reineking |first=Jim |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/worldcup/2018/06/11/world-cup-2018-notable-teams-failed-qualify-usmnt-italy/675930002/ |title=FIFA World Cup 2018: Notable teams that failed to qualify |website=[[USAToday.com]] |publisher=Gannett Company |accessdate=26 December 2018 |date=11 June 2018}}</ref> In the fall of 2018, he returned to the Ghana team for the first time since the qualifying failure and made two appearances in [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group F|2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualifying]] as the Black Stars finalized a spot at the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Narkortu Teye |first=Prince |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-kenya-qualify-for-2019-africa-cup-of-nations-as-sierra/xp3so8k13vak15qd5pqanzf4w |title=Ghana & Kenya qualify for 2019 Africa Cup of Nations as Sierra Leone get kicked out from qualifiers |website=Goal.com |publisher=Goal |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|1 March 2020|<ref name=WFprofile/><ref name=\"sw\"/><ref name=MLSprofile/>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Cup<ref group=lower-alpha>Appearances in the [[U.S. Open Cup]]</ref>\n!colspan=2|Continental\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=8|[[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis|ES Tunis]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2009\u201310]]\n|[[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|CLP-1]]\n|18||2||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2013||18||2\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2010\u201311]]\n|CLP-1\n|17||0||0||0||10{{efn|Appearances in the [[CAF Champions League]]|name=CL}}||1||colspan=2|\u2013||27||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2011\u201312]]\n|CLP-1\n|16||0||0||0||11{{efn|name=CL}}||1||2{{efn|Appearances in the [[FIFA Club World Cup]]}}||0||29||1\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2012\u201313]]\n|CLP-1\n|17||3||0||0||11{{efn|name=CL}}||0||colspan=2|\u2013||28||3\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2013\u201314]]\n|CLP-1\n|27||4||0||0||10{{efn|name=CL}}||0||colspan=2|\u2013||37||4\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2014\u201315]]\n|CLP-1\n|23||2|||0||0||6{{efn|name=CL}}||2||colspan=2|\u2013||29||4\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|2015\u201316]]\n|CLP-1\n|0||0||0||0||4{{efn|One appearance in the CAF Champions League, three appearances and on